# 📘 Module 2 — Inner Classes & Inheritance (Super Class)

## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Inner Class (Nested Class)

> [!NOTE]
> **Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology):**
> An **Inner Class** (also called a **Nested Class**) in Java is a class that is declared as a member of another class or within a block of code. The class that encloses the inner class is called the **Outer Class** (or **Enclosing Class**). Inner classes were introduced in **JDK 1.1** and are a fundamental way to logically group classes that are only used in one place, increasing encapsulation and producing more readable, maintainable code.

#### 🏠 Conceptual Analogy — "The House and Its Rooms"

Imagine a **House** (the Outer Class). Inside the house, there are several **Rooms** (the Inner Classes). Each room:
- Belongs exclusively to that house (cannot exist independently).
- Has **automatic access** to all the furniture, wiring, and plumbing of the house (members of the outer class).
- Is hidden from the outside world unless the house owner opens the door (access modifiers).

This perfectly mirrors an inner class — it cannot exist without its outer class instance and can directly access all members (even private ones) of the outer class.

---

### 1.2 Inheritance and the Super Class

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology):**
> **Inheritance** is the OOP mechanism by which one class (called the **Sub Class**, **Derived Class**, or **Child Class**) acquires the properties and behaviors (fields and methods) of another class (called the **Super Class**, **Base Class**, or **Parent Class**).
> The **`super`** keyword in Java is a reference variable that refers to the **immediate parent class object**. It is primarily used to differentiate between members of the sub class and the super class when they share the same name, and to invoke the parent class constructor.

#### 🧬 Conceptual Analogy — "Genetics and Family Traits"

Think of a **Child** (Sub Class) and their **Parent** (Super Class):
- The child **inherits** physical traits (eye color, height) and behavioral patterns (speech style) from the parent.
- However, the child can **override** certain traits — for example, having a different hairstyle while still inheriting the parent's eye color (Method Overriding).
- The child can explicitly refer to the parent's version of a trait using the word *"Mom's recipe"* or *"Dad's car"* — this is exactly what **`super`** does in Java: it refers to the parent's version.
- A child must always acknowledge the parent's existence first — represented in Java by the **`super()`** constructor call.

---

### 1.3 KTU Syllabus Highlights

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Examination Points:**
> - The **4 categories** of inner classes (Member, Static Nested, Local, Anonymous).
> - How inner classes access outer class members (including `private`).
> - Compilation behavior: each inner class produces a separate `.class` file named `OuterClass$InnerClass.class`.
> - The **3 distinct uses** of the `super` keyword.
> - **Constructor chaining** in inheritance hierarchies.
> - Access modifiers and visibility rules of inner classes.

---

### 1.4 Classification Overview

| Concept | Primary Purpose | Lifetime Dependency |
|---|---|---|
| Member Inner Class | General-purpose nested class | Depends on Outer instance |
| Static Nested Class | Group helper classes (no outer instance needed) | Independent of Outer instance |
| Local Inner Class | Class scoped to a method/block | Scope-limited |
| Anonymous Inner Class | One-time implementation (e.g., event handling) | Expression-scoped |
| `super` keyword | Access parent's hidden/overridden members | Compile-time reference |
| `super()` call | Invoke parent constructor | First statement in constructor |

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 🔍 Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 The Four Types of Inner Classes

### Type 1 — Member Inner Class (Non-Static)

A class declared **at the member level** of another class (just like a field or method).

```java
class Outer {
    private int data = 10;

    class Inner {
        void display() {
            System.out.println("data = " + data); // Direct access to private field
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Rules:**
- **Cannot** declare `static` members (except `static final` constants).
- Requires an **outer class instance** to be instantiated:
  `Outer outer = new Outer();`
  `Outer.Inner inner = outer.new Inner();`
- Compiles to: `Outer$Inner.class`

---

### Type 2 — Static Nested Class

A `static` class declared at the member level of another class.

```java
class Outer {
    private static int count = 100;
    private String name = "KTU";

    static class StaticNested {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("count = " + count); // ✅ can access static
            // System.out.println(name); ❌ cannot access non-static
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Rules:**
- **Can** declare both static and non-static members.
- **Cannot** directly access non-static members of the outer class.
- Instantiation does **not** require an outer instance:
  `Outer.StaticNested obj = new Outer.StaticNested();`
- Compiles to: `Outer$StaticNested.class`

---

### Type 3 — Local Inner Class

A class declared **inside a method, constructor, or an initializer block**.

```java
class Outer {
    void calculate() {
        final int limit = 50;

        class LocalHelper {
            void check(int n) {
                if (n > limit) System.out.println("Exceeds limit");
            }
        }

        LocalHelper helper = new LocalHelper();
        helper.check(75);
    }
}
```

**Key Rules:**
- Scope is **limited to the enclosing block**.
- Can access `final` (or **effectively final**) local variables of the enclosing block.
- **Cannot** be declared `public`, `private`, `protected`, or `static`.
- Compiles to: `Outer$1LocalHelper.class` (numbered, since the class has no name identifier outside the block)

---

### Type 4 — Anonymous Inner Class

A **nameless** class declared and instantiated in a single expression — typically used to provide a one-time implementation of an interface or abstract class.

```java
interface Greeting {
    void sayHello();
}

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Greeting g = new Greeting() {
            @Override
            public void sayHello() {
                System.out.println("Hello from Anonymous Class!");
            }
        };
        g.sayHello();
    }
}
```

**Key Rules:**
- Has **no class name**.
- Must either **extend a class OR implement an interface** (not both, and not multiple interfaces).
- Used extensively in **event handling** (Swing/JavaFX), **callbacks**, and **lambda-like** scenarios.
- Compiles to: `Outer$1.class`, `Outer$2.class`, etc.

---

## 2.2 The `super` Keyword — Three Distinct Uses

### Use 1 — `super.memberName` (Access Hidden Fields)

When the sub class declares a field with the **same name** as the super class, the sub class field **hides** the super class field.

```java
class Super {
    int value = 100;
}

class Sub extends Super {
    int value = 200;

    void print() {
        System.out.println("Sub value   = " + value);       // 200
        System.out.println("Super value = " + super.value); // 100
    }
}
```

### Use 2 — `super.methodName()` (Invoke Overridden Methods)

```java
class Super {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Super.display()");
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    @Override
    void display() {
        super.display(); // explicitly call parent version
        System.out.println("Sub.display()");
    }
}
```

### Use 3 — `super(arguments)` (Invoke Parent Constructor)

```java
class Super {
    Super(int x) {
        System.out.println("Super constructor: " + x);
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    Sub() {
        super(42); // MUST be the first statement
        System.out.println("Sub constructor");
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Constructor Chaining Rule (KTU High-Yield):**
> If the sub class constructor **does not explicitly** call `super(...)` or `this(...)`, the compiler **automatically inserts** a call to the **no-argument constructor** of the parent. If the parent has no no-argument constructor, a **compilation error** occurs.

---

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Construct | Syntax Pattern | Visibility | Outer Instance Needed? | Compiled File Name |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Member Inner Class | `class Outer { class Inner { } }` | All 4 modifiers allowed | Yes | `Outer$Inner.class` |
| Static Nested Class | `class Outer { static class Nested { } }` | All 4 modifiers allowed | No | `Outer$Nested.class` |
| Local Inner Class | declared inside method/block | No modifiers allowed | Yes (implicit) | `Outer$1LocalName.class` |
| Anonymous Inner Class | `new Interface() { ... }` or `new SuperClass(args) { ... }` | N/A | Depends on context | `Outer$1.class` |
| `super.field` | `super.variableName` | Compile-time | N/A | N/A |
| `super.method()` | `super.methodName(args)` | Compile-time | N/A | N/A |
| `super(args)` | `super(arg1, arg2, ...)` | First statement only | N/A | N/A |

### Access Modifier Matrix for Inner Classes

| Inner Class Type | Can be `private`? | Can be `protected`? | Can be `static`? | Can access outer `private` members? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Member Inner | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Static Nested | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ (implicitly) | ✅ (static only) |
| Local Inner | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Anonymous | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |

---

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

> [!NOTE]
> **Where These Concepts Are Used in Industry:**
> - **GUI Frameworks (JavaFX, Swing):** Anonymous inner classes are heavily used for event listeners (e.g., `button.setOnAction(new EventHandler<>() { ... })`).
> - **Data Structures:** `java.util.Map.Entry` is implemented as a static nested interface inside the `Map` interface.
> - **Builder Pattern:** Static nested classes like `OuterClass.Builder` are used to construct complex immutable objects.
> - **Framework Design:** Spring and Android use inner classes for callback interfaces and adapter patterns.
> - **Inheritance + `super`:** Template Method design pattern relies on `super.method()` calls to invoke base class hooks.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 🧮 Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Walkthroughs

## 3.1 Analytical Walkthrough — How an Inner Class Accesses Outer Members

### Step-by-Step Logic

**Step 1 — The compiler injects a synthetic field.**
When the Java compiler processes a non-static inner class, it automatically adds a **synthetic (hidden) field** named `this$0` of type `Outer`, and a synthetic constructor `Outer$Inner(Outer outer)` that initializes `this$0`.

**Step 2 — The reference is bound at instantiation.**
When you write `outer.new Inner()`, the compiler passes `outer` to the synthetic constructor, binding the inner class instance to that specific outer instance.

**Step 3 — All member accesses are routed through `this$0`.**
Every time the inner class references an outer class member, the compiler rewrites it as `this$0.memberName`.

### Conceptual Derivation

Let us trace the statement:

```java
System.out.println("data = " + data);
```

inside the `Inner` class of the `Outer` class.

The compiler conceptually rewrites this as:

```java
System.out.println("data = " + Outer.this.data);
```

$$
\text{Access Path} = \text{InnerObject}.\text{this\$0}.\text{OuterMember}
$$

$$
\text{where } \text{this\$0} = \text{the enclosing Outer class instance}
$$

This is precisely why a non-static inner class **cannot exist without an outer instance** — the `this$0` reference would be `null`.

---

## 3.2 Analytical Walkthrough — Constructor Chaining with `super()`

Consider a three-level inheritance hierarchy: `GrandParent` → `Parent` → `Child`.

```java
class GrandParent {
    GrandParent() {
        System.out.println("GrandParent constructor");
    }
}

class Parent extends GrandParent {
    Parent() {
        System.out.println("Parent constructor");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        System.out.println("Child constructor");
    }
}
```

### Execution Trace

When `new Child()` is invoked, the following chain executes **top-down**:

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\text{Step 1: } \texttt{new Child()} \text{ is called.} \\
&\text{Step 2: Compiler checks — does Child's constructor call this() or super()?} \\
&\text{Step 3: No — so compiler auto-inserts } \texttt{super();} \text{ as first statement.} \\
&\text{Step 4: Parent's no-arg constructor runs.} \\
&\text{Step 5: Compiler checks Parent — no super()/this() call.} \\
&\text{Step 6: Compiler auto-inserts } \texttt{super();} \text{ in Parent.} \\
&\text{Step 7: GrandParent's no-arg constructor runs.} \\
&\text{Step 8: GrandParent body finishes. Prints: "GrandParent constructor"} \\
&\text{Step 9: Parent body resumes. Prints: "Parent constructor"} \\
&\text{Step 10: Child body resumes. Prints: "Child constructor"}
\end{aligned}
$$

### Output

```
GrandParent constructor
Parent constructor
Child constructor
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Mnemonic for Students:** "Grandparents are **built first**, then parents, then children" — the constructor chain flows from the **topmost ancestor** down to the **most derived class**.

---

## 3.3 Analytical Walkthrough — Resolving Name Conflicts with `super`

Consider this hierarchy:

```java
class Vehicle {
    int speed = 60;
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle is running at " + speed + " km/h");
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    int speed = 120;

    @Override
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Car speed (this.speed)  = " + this.speed);
        System.out.println("Vehicle speed (super.speed) = " + super.speed);
        super.run(); // explicitly invoke parent's run()
        System.out.println("Car is running at " + this.speed + " km/h");
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Resolution

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\texttt{this.speed} \rightarrow \texttt{120} \quad \text{(Car's field, hides parent's)} \\
&\texttt{super.speed} \rightarrow \texttt{60} \quad \text{(Vehicle's hidden field)} \\
&\texttt{super.run()} \rightarrow \text{invokes } \texttt{Vehicle.run()} \\
&\texttt{this.run()} \rightarrow \text{would invoke } \texttt{Car.run()} \text{ (recursion if used here)}
\end{aligned}
$$

### Output when `car.run()` is called

```
Car speed (this.speed)  = 120
Vehicle speed (super.speed) = 60
Vehicle is running at 60 km/h
Car is running at 120 km/h
```

---

## 3.4 Analytical Walkthrough — Anonymous Inner Class Compilation

```java
abstract class Shape {
    abstract void draw();
}

class Canvas {
    void render() {
        Shape circle = new Shape() {
            @Override
            void draw() {
                System.out.println("Drawing a circle");
            }
        };
        circle.draw();
    }
}
```

### Compilation Steps

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\text{Step 1: Compiler sees } \texttt{new Shape() \{ ... \}}. \\
&\text{Step 2: Generates a synthetic class file named } \texttt{Canvas\$1.class}. \\
&\text{Step 3: This class } \texttt{extends Shape} \text{ and implements } \texttt{draw()}. \\
&\text{Step 4: The reference } \texttt{circle} \text{ is of static type } \texttt{Shape}, \\
&\text{dynamic type } \texttt{Canvas\$1}. \\
&\text{Step 5: At runtime, JVM uses dynamic dispatch — calls } \texttt{Canvas\$1.draw()}.
\end{aligned}
$$

---

## 3.5 Comparative Analytical Matrix

| Feature | Member Inner | Static Nested | Local Inner | Anonymous |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Has a class name | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Can declare constructors | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Can extend a class | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (exactly one) |
| Can implement interfaces | ✅ Yes (multiple) | ✅ Yes (multiple) | ✅ Yes (multiple) | ✅ Yes (exactly one) |
| Access to enclosing locals | N/A | N/A | ✅ Final/effectively-final only | ✅ Final/effectively-final only |
| Common use case | Helper classes | Builder/utility | Algorithm-specific helpers | Event handlers, callbacks |

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
