# 🎯 KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1: `[KTU University Exam — May 2024]`
**Differentiate between a static nested class and a member inner class in Java. Mention any two differences.**

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | Member Inner Class | Static Nested Class |
|---|---|---|
| Declaration | Non-static class inside outer | Declared with `static` keyword |
| Outer instance required | Yes — needs `outer.new Inner()` | No — can be instantiated directly |
| Access to outer members | Can access all (including private) | Can access only static members |
| Can declare static members | No (except `static final` constants) | Yes |
| Compiled filename | `Outer$Inner.class` | `Outer$Nested.class` |

**(Any two differences — 3 marks)**

---

### Question 2: `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`
**Explain the use of the `super` keyword in Java with suitable examples.**

**Model Answer:**

The `super` keyword in Java is a reference variable used to refer to the **immediate parent class**. It has **three primary uses:**

1. **`super.field`** — Accesses the parent class field when it is hidden by a sub class field with the same name.
   ```java
   super.value;
   ```

2. **`super.method()`** — Invokes the parent class version of an overridden method.
   ```java
   super.display();
   ```

3. **`super(args)`** — Calls a parent class constructor. Must be the **first statement** in the sub class constructor.
   ```java
   super(10);
   ```

If no explicit call is made, the compiler inserts a no-argument `super()` automatically. **(3 marks)**

---

## Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each)

### 🅰️ Question A: `[KTU University Exam — July 2024]`

**a)** Explain the different types of inner classes in Java with examples. **(7 marks)**

**b)** With a suitable Java program, demonstrate how the `super` keyword is used to invoke a parent class constructor and to access a hidden member of the super class. **(7 marks)**

---

#### ✅ Solution for Question A — Part (a)

**Types of Inner Classes in Java:**

**1. Member Inner Class (Non-static nested class)**

A class declared as a member of the outer class. It can access all members (including private) of the outer class.

```java
class University {
    private String name = "KTU Kerala";

    class Department { // Member inner class
        void display() {
            System.out.println("University: " + name);
        }
    }
}

class MainA {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        University u = new University();
        University.Department d = u.new Department();
        d.display();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
University: KTU Kerala
```

**2. Static Nested Class**

A static class declared inside another class. It can access only the static members of the outer class.

```java
class University {
    static String location = "Thiruvananthapuram";

    static class Campus { // Static nested class
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Campus location: " + location);
        }
    }
}

class MainB {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        University.Campus c = new University.Campus();
        c.show();
    }
}
```

**3. Local Inner Class**

A class declared inside a method or block. Its scope is limited to the enclosing block.

```java
class Calculator {
    void compute() {
        class Helper { // Local inner class
            int square(int n) { return n * n; }
        }
        Helper h = new Helper();
        System.out.println("Square of 5: " + h.square(5));
    }
}
```

**4. Anonymous Inner Class**

A nameless class used for a single-use implementation, typically for interfaces or abstract classes.

```java
abstract class Shape {
    abstract void draw();
}

class MainC {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape s = new Shape() {
            @Override
            void draw() {
                System.out.println("Drawing a triangle");
            }
        };
        s.draw();
    }
}
```

**(Each type explained with example — 7 marks: ~1.75 marks each)**

---

#### ✅ Solution for Question A — Part (b)

**Program demonstrating `super` keyword:**

```java
class Employee {
    String name = "Rahul";
    double salary = 50000.0;

    Employee(String name, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
        System.out.println("Employee constructor called");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Employee Name: " + name + ", Salary: " + salary);
    }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    String name = "Arjun"; // Hides parent's name
    String department;

    Manager(String name, double salary, String dept) {
        super(name, salary); // ✅ Invokes parent constructor (1st statement)
        this.department = dept;
        System.out.println("Manager constructor called");
    }

    @Override
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Manager Name: " + name);               // this.name
        System.out.println("Employee Name: " + super.name);        // super.name
        System.out.println("Department: " + department);
        super.display(); // ✅ Calls overridden parent method
    }
}

class TestSuper {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Manager m = new Manager("Vivek", 85000.0, "Computer Science");
        m.display();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-step Explanation:**

1. `new Manager(...)` invokes the Manager constructor.
2. **First statement** `super(name, salary)` explicitly calls `Employee(String, double)`.
3. `Employee` constructor sets the inherited fields.
4. After `super()` returns, the rest of the Manager constructor body runs.
5. `display()` is overridden; it uses `super.name` to access the **hidden** parent's field, and `super.display()` to invoke the **overridden** parent method.

**Output:**
```
Employee constructor called
Manager constructor called
Manager Name: Arjun
Employee Name: Vivek
Department: Computer Science
Employee Name: Vivek, Salary: 85000.0
```

**(Full program + explanation + output — 7 marks)**

---

### 🅱️ Question B: `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`

**a)** What are the restrictions on declaring static members inside a member inner class? Justify with an example. **(7 marks)**

**b)** Explain constructor chaining in multilevel inheritance with a Java program. Show the order of execution of constructors. **(7 marks)**

---

#### ✅ Solution for Question B — Part (a)

**Restrictions on Static Members in Member Inner Classes:**

According to the **Java Language Specification (JLS §8.1.3)**, a non-static inner class **cannot declare static members**, with the sole exception of **compile-time constants** (i.e., `static final` primitives or `String` initialized with a constant expression).

**Why this restriction exists:**
A non-static inner class is logically tied to an outer class instance. Static members, however, belong to the **class itself**, not to any instance. Allowing static fields/methods in an instance-bound inner class would break this fundamental OOP invariant.

**Example demonstrating the restriction:**

```java
class Outer {
    int x = 10;

    class Inner {
        // int count = 0;          // ❌ Cannot declare static field
        // static void show() {}   // ❌ Cannot declare static method

        static final int LIMIT = 100;     // ✅ Compile-time constant — allowed
        static final String MSG = "OK";   // ✅ Compile-time constant — allowed

        void display() {
            System.out.println("x = " + x + ", LIMIT = " + LIMIT);
        }
    }
}
```

**However, in a Static Nested Class — full static members are allowed:**

```java
class Outer {
    static int count = 50;

    static class Nested {
        static int nestedCount = 100;     // ✅ Allowed
        static void show() {              // ✅ Allowed
            System.out.println("count = " + count);
        }
    }
}
```

**Summary Table:**

| Member Type | Member Inner Class | Static Nested Class |
|---|---|---|
| Non-static field | ✅ | ✅ |
| Static field | ❌ (except `static final` constants) | ✅ |
| Static method | ❌ | ✅ |
| `static final` constant | ✅ | ✅ |

**(7 marks: explanation + example + justification)**

---

#### ✅ Solution for Question B — Part (b)

**Constructor Chaining in Multilevel Inheritance:**

```java
class GrandParent {
    GrandParent() {
        System.out.println("1. GrandParent constructor");
    }
}

class Parent extends GrandParent {
    Parent() {
        System.out.println("2. Parent constructor");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        System.out.println("3. Child constructor");
    }
}

class DemoChain {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child c = new Child();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-step Order of Execution:**

| Step | Action | Output |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `new Child()` called | — |
| 2 | Compiler auto-inserts `super()` in `Child()` | — |
| 3 | `Parent()` body starts | — |
| 4 | Compiler auto-inserts `super()` in `Parent()` | — |
| 5 | `GrandParent()` body executes | `1. GrandParent constructor` |
| 6 | `Parent()` body resumes | `2. Parent constructor` |
| 7 | `Child()` body resumes | `3. Child constructor` |

**Output:**
```
1. GrandParent constructor
2. Parent constructor
3. Child constructor
```

**Key Rule:**
> The constructor chain always executes from the **topmost ancestor** down to the **most derived class**, regardless of where `new` is called. This ensures that inherited fields are initialized **before** the sub class constructor body runs.

**(7 marks: program + execution order table + rule explanation)**

