## 📋 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> ✅ **Rapid Revision Checklist:**

- [ ] Inner classes are **4 types**: Member (non-static), Static Nested, Local, Anonymous.
- [ ] Member inner classes require an **outer instance**; static nested classes do not.
- [ ] Anonymous inner classes are **declared and instantiated in one expression** — no class name, no constructors.
- [ ] Each inner class produces a **separate `.class` file** named `Outer$InnerName.class`.
- [ ] Local inner classes can only access **final or effectively final** local variables.
- [ ] The `super` keyword has **3 uses**: `super.field`, `super.method()`, `super(args)`.
- [ ] `super(args)` **must be the first statement** in a sub class constructor.
- [ ] If no `super()` or `this()` is explicitly written, the compiler **auto-inserts** `super()` (no-arg version).
- [ ] If the parent has **no no-argument constructor** and the child doesn't call `super(args)`, **compilation fails**.
- [ ] Constructor chaining executes **top-down**: grandparent → parent → child.
- [ ] A non-static inner class **cannot declare static members** (except `static final` constants).
- [ ] `super` **cannot be used in static methods** or `static` blocks.
- [ ] Anonymous classes can **extend one class OR implement one interface** — not both.
- [ ] **Mnemonic for `super`**: *S*uper — *S*eeks — *S*uper class members.

