# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Access Matrix

## 2.1 The Three Pillars of Access Control — A Structured Breakdown

### 2.1.1 `private` Members
- Accessible **only inside the class** that declares them.
- Strictest form of encapsulation.
- Even derived classes **cannot** access private members of the base class directly (in C++).
- **In Java**, the `private` restriction is enforced at the class level — inner/nested classes can access private members of the enclosing class.

### 2.1.2 `protected` Members
- Accessible within the **declaring class** itself.
- Accessible within any **derived class** (via inheritance, regardless of package/namespace in C++; with package-level nuances in Java).
- Accessible within the **same package** (Java-specific behaviour).
- **Not** accessible from unrelated classes in the global scope.

### 2.1.3 `public` Members
- Accessible from **anywhere** — within the class, derived classes, same package, unrelated classes, and even external code.
- Weakest encapsulation; should be used sparingly for true interface contracts.

## 2.2 The KTU High-Yield Access Matrix (Master Reference Table)

The following table is **the single most important reference** for KTU examinations on access specifiers. Memorize it thoroughly.

| Access Context                              | `private` | `protected` | `public` |
|---------------------------------------------|:---------:|:-----------:|:--------:|
| **Within the same class**                   |    ✅     |     ✅      |    ✅    |
| **Derived class (same package / namespace)**|    ❌     |     ✅      |    ✅    |
| **Derived class (different package — Java)**|    ❌     |     ✅ (via inheritance only) | ✅ |
| **Non-derived class (same package — Java)** |    ❌     |     ✅      |    ✅    |
| **Non-derived class (different package)**   |    ❌     |     ❌      |    ✅    |
| **Outside the class hierarchy (C++)**       |    ❌     |     ❌      |    ✅    |
| **Friend class / friend function (C++)**    |    ✅     |     ✅      |    ✅    |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Java-Specific Twist (Frequently Tested):**
> In Java, a non-derived class within the **same package** can access `protected` members of another class. However, a derived class in a **different package** can only access `protected` members **through inheritance** — meaning it must access them on an object reference of its own type (or a subclass), **not** on a reference of the base class type. This subtle rule catches many students off-guard in KTU exams.

## 2.3 The `protected` Keyword Across Languages — Detailed Rules

### 2.3.1 C++ Behaviour
- Declared using the `protected:` label inside a class definition.
- Accessible to **derived classes** and **friend classes/functions** of either the base or derived class.
- **Not accessible** to other classes, even if they are in the same namespace.
- Can be combined with `virtual` for polymorphic protected methods.

### 2.3.2 Java Behaviour
- Declared using the `protected` keyword before a member.
- Accessible to:
  1. The declaring class.
  2. Any subclass (in any package), but **only through inheritance** (i.e., on `this` or subclass-type references).
  3. Any class in the **same package** (treated like package-private access).
- **Not accessible** to classes outside the package that are not subclasses.

### 2.3.3 C# Behaviour
- Declared using the `protected` keyword.
- Accessible only within the declaring class and its derived classes.
- C# does **not** extend protected access to the same package/assembly (a key difference from Java).
- C# also offers `protected internal` (protected OR same-assembly) and `private protected` (protected AND same-assembly).

## 2.4 Why `protected` Exists — The Design Rationale

The `protected` access level was introduced to solve a real engineering problem:

> **"How can a base class expose its internal machinery to its descendants for the purpose of extension, without exposing it to the entire world?"**

Consider a `Shape` base class with an internal buffer that stores the vertices of the shape. A derived class `Polygon` may need to manipulate this buffer to compute the centroid. If the buffer is `private`, `Polygon` cannot touch it. If it is `public`, any random code could corrupt it. **`protected` is the perfect middle ground.**

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Domain                          | Use of `protected`                                                     |
|---------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **GUI Frameworks**              | Base widget classes expose `protected` event hooks to derived controls |
| **Game Engines**                | Base `Entity` class exposes `protected` transform data to game objects |
| **Database ORMs**               | Base `Model` class exposes `protected` fields for ORM column mapping   |
| **Network Protocol Libraries**  | Base `Packet` class exposes `protected` header fields to parsers       |
| **Compiler Design**             | Base `ASTNode` exposes `protected` children list to derived node types |

## 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept                         | Rule / Formula (Verbatim for Exam Use)                                |
|---------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| C++ Protected Declaration       | `protected: <member_list>;`                                           |
| Java Protected Declaration       | `protected <type> <name>;` or `protected <returnType> <method>();`    |
| C++ Friend + Protected          | Friend functions/classes of base OR derived class can access protected |
| Java Same-Package Rule          | `protected` ≡ package-private for non-subclasses in the same package  |
| Java Cross-Package Subclass     | Access only via `this` or subclass-type references, not base-type ref  |
| Default (Java)                  | Package-private (no keyword)                                           |
| C++ Struct Default              | `public`                                                               |
| C++ Class Default               | `private`                                                              |
