# 3. Step-by-Step Code Analysis & Analytical Walkthroughs

## 3.1 Analytical Walkthrough #1: Basic `protected` Access in C++

### Step 1: Define the Base Class with a `protected` Member

```cpp
class Account {
private:
    double pin;              // Only Account can touch this

protected:
    double balance;          // Account and its children can touch this

public:
    int accountNumber;       // Anyone can touch this

    Account(double b) : balance(b), pin(1234), accountNumber(1001) {}
};
```

### Step 2: Derive a Child Class that Accesses the `protected` Member

```cpp
class SavingsAccount : public Account {
public:
    SavingsAccount(double b) : Account(b) {}

    void addInterest(double rate) {
        balance = balance + (balance * rate);   // ✅ LEGAL: derived class accesses protected
        // pin = 9999;                           // ❌ ILLEGAL: pin is private to Account
        // accountNumber = 2002;                 // ✅ LEGAL: public, accessible everywhere
    }

    void display() {
        std::cout << "Balance: " << balance << std::endl;
    }
};
```

### Step 3: Test from a Non-Derived Class (main function)

```cpp
int main() {
    SavingsAccount sa(1000.0);
    sa.addInterest(0.05);
    sa.display();            // Prints: Balance: 1050

    // sa.balance = 99999;   // ❌ ILLEGAL: balance is protected, not accessible from main
    // sa.pin = 0000;        // ❌ ILLEGAL: pin is private
    sa.accountNumber = 2002; // ✅ LEGAL: public
    return 0;
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Analysis

| Step | Code Action                              | Compilation Result | Reasoning                                                  |
|:----:|------------------------------------------|:------------------:|------------------------------------------------------------|
|  1   | `balance = balance + (balance * rate);`  | ✅ Compiles         | `balance` is `protected`; `SavingsAccount` is a derived class |
|  2   | `pin = 9999;`                            | ❌ Compile error    | `pin` is `private` to `Account`; not visible in derived class |
|  3   | `sa.balance = 99999;`                    | ❌ Compile error    | `balance` is `protected`; not accessible from non-derived `main` |
|  4   | `sa.accountNumber = 2002;`               | ✅ Compiles         | `accountNumber` is `public`; accessible from anywhere      |

---

## 3.2 Analytical Walkthrough #2: Java's `protected` Cross-Package Rule

### Step 1: Create the Base Class in Package `bank.core`

```java
package bank.core;

public class BankAccount {
    private double pin = 1234;          // only BankAccount
    protected double balance = 5000;   // BankAccount, same-package, AND subclasses
    public String bankName = "KTU Bank";

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
```

### Step 2: Create a Derived Class in a DIFFERENT Package `bank.derivatives`

```java
package bank.derivatives;
import bank.core.BankAccount;

public class PremiumAccount extends BankAccount {

    public void creditInterest(double rate) {
        balance = balance + (balance * rate);  // ✅ LEGAL: subclass accessing protected member
        // pin = 0000;                           // ❌ ILLEGAL: pin is private
    }

    public void showBalance() {
        System.out.println("Balance: " + balance);  // ✅ LEGAL
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Test the Subtle Java Rule — Base-Type vs Subclass-Type References

```java
package bank.derivatives;
import bank.core.BankAccount;

public class TestAccess {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PremiumAccount pa = new PremiumAccount();
        pa.creditInterest(0.10);
        pa.showBalance();                // ✅ LEGAL: public method

        // Accessing protected through a base-type reference from outside the package:
        BankAccount baseRef = new PremiumAccount();
        // System.out.println(baseRef.balance);  // ❌ ILLEGAL: cross-package, non-inheriting access
        // The rule: a subclass in a different package can only access protected members
        // on references of its own type (or a subclass), not on a base-type reference.

        System.out.println(pa.balance);  // ⚠️ LEGAL only because 'pa' is PremiumAccount type
                                          //     and we are inside a subclass file
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Analysis

| Step | Code Action                              | Compilation Result | Reasoning                                                                 |
|:----:|------------------------------------------|:------------------:|---------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|  1   | `balance = balance + ...` in subclass    | ✅ Compiles         | Derived class in different package accessing inherited protected member   |
|  2   | `pin = 0000;` in subclass                | ❌ Compile error    | `pin` is `private` to `BankAccount`                                       |
|  3   | `baseRef.balance` in non-subclass context| ❌ Compile error    | Cross-package, non-inheriting access to `protected`                       |
|  4   | `pa.balance` inside PremiumAccount file  | ✅ Compiles         | Accessing protected member on a same-type reference from within subclass  |

> [!NOTE]
> **The most tested nuance in KTU exams:**
> In Java, when a subclass exists in a different package, it can only access a `protected` member **through an inherited context** (i.e., on `this` or on a reference of the subclass type), **not on a reference of the base class type from a client class**. This is a classic J2SE specification rule.

---

## 3.3 Analytical Walkthrough #3: C++ Multi-Level Inheritance with `protected`

### Step 1: Grandparent Class

```cpp
class LivingThing {
protected:
    int energyLevel;
public:
    LivingThing() : energyLevel(100) {}
    void showEnergy() { std::cout << "Energy: " << energyLevel << std::endl; }
};
```

### Step 2: Parent Class (intermediate)

```cpp
class Animal : public LivingThing {
protected:
    bool isWarmBlooded;
public:
    Animal(bool warm) : isWarmBlooded(warm) {}
};
```

### Step 3: Child Class (grandchild of LivingThing)

```cpp
class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    Dog() : Animal(true) {}

    void run() {
        energyLevel = energyLevel - 10;  // ✅ LEGAL: energyLevel is protected in LivingThing,
                                         //    and Dog is a transitive descendant
        // isWarmBlooded = false;        // ✅ LEGAL: protected in Animal, Dog is a child
        std::cout << "Dog ran! Energy now: " << energyLevel << std::endl;
    }
};
```

### Step 4: Test from Outside

```cpp
int main() {
    Dog d;
    d.run();
    // d.energyLevel = 50;   // ❌ ILLEGAL: protected, not accessible from main
    // d.isWarmBlooded = false; // ❌ ILLEGAL: protected
    d.showEnergy();          // ✅ LEGAL: public method
    return 0;
}
```

### Analytical Summary Table

| Access Attempt                       | From         | Legal?  | Why                                              |
|--------------------------------------|--------------|:-------:|--------------------------------------------------|
| `energyLevel` in `Dog::run()`        | Grandchild   |   ✅    | Protected in grandparent, Dog is a descendant    |
| `isWarmBlooded` in `Dog::run()`      | Child        |   ✅    | Protected in parent, Dog is a child              |
| `d.energyLevel` in `main`            | Non-relative |   ❌    | Protected, not accessible from outside hierarchy |
| `d.showEnergy()` in `main`           | Anyone       |   ✅    | Public method, accessible everywhere            |

