## 3.4 Analytical Walkthrough #4: `protected` + `friend` Function in C++

This is a classic KTU 14-mark question pattern.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
class Base {
private:
    int secret = 42;
protected:
    int shared = 100;
public:
    friend void externalFunction(Base& b);  // friend declaration
};

void externalFunction(Base& b) {
    std::cout << "Secret: " << b.secret << std::endl;   // ✅ friend can access private
    std::cout << "Shared: " << b.shared << std::endl;   // ✅ friend can access protected
}

int main() {
    Base b;
    externalFunction(b);
    return 0;
}
```

### Key Insight

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Friend functions and friend classes** in C++ can access **all** members of the class that befriends them — regardless of whether those members are `private`, `protected`, or `public`. This is a **deliberate backdoor** provided by C++ for tight coupling scenarios (operator overloading, debugging hooks, etc.).

---

## 3.5 Comparative Algorithm: Choosing the Right Access Specifier

Use this decision tree to pick the correct access level in KTU design questions:

$$
\text{Decision Tree} = \begin{cases}
\text{Only this class?} & \rightarrow \texttt{private} \\
\text{This class + its descendants?} & \rightarrow \texttt{protected} \\
\text{This class + its descendants + same package (Java)?} & \rightarrow \texttt{protected} \\
\text{Everyone?} & \rightarrow \texttt{public} \\
\text{Tight coupling with one external helper?} & \rightarrow \texttt{friend (C++ only)}
\end{cases}
$$
