## 4.4 Block-Level Functional Architecture: The Three-Layer Encapsulation Model

When designing large OOP systems, the `protected` access specifier fits into a three-layer encapsulation model:

```mermaid
graph LR
    L1["LAYER 1: PUBLIC INTERFACE\nAPI exposed to external clients\nConstructors, getters, public methods"]:::pubLayer
    L2["LAYER 2: PROTECTED EXTENSION POINTS\nHooks for derived classes\nTemplate method pattern support"]:::protLayer
    L3["LAYER 3: PRIVATE INTERNAL STATE\nHidden implementation details\nEncapsulated invariants, buffers"]:::privLayer

    L1 -->|"delegates to"| L2
    L2 -->|"manipulates"| L3
    L3 -.->|"never directly visible to"| L1

    EXT["External Client Code"]:::client
    DER["Derived Class"]:::derived

    EXT -->|uses| L1
    DER -->|overrides and accesses| L2
    DER -.->|cannot directly access| L3

    classDef pubLayer fill:#2563eb,stroke:#2563eb,stroke-width:2px,color:#ffffff
    classDef protLayer fill:#16a34a,stroke:#16a34a,stroke-width:2px,color:#ffffff
    classDef privLayer fill:#dc2626,stroke:#dc2626,stroke-width:2px,color:#ffffff
    classDef client fill:#6b7280,stroke:#6b7280,stroke-width:2px,color:#ffffff
    classDef derived fill:#7c3aed,stroke:#7c3aed,stroke-width:2px,color:#ffffff
```

**Engineering Insight:**
- **Layer 1 (Public):** The contract with the outside world.
- **Layer 2 (Protected):** The extension contract with future developers who will derive new classes.
- **Layer 3 (Private):** The sacred internals that must never leak, even to derived classes.
