## 5.1 PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question A1. `[KTU University Exam — May 2024]`
**Define the `protected` access specifier in C++. How does it differ from `private` and `public`?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The `protected` access specifier in C++ is an access control keyword that makes a class member accessible in **two contexts**:
1. Within the **class itself** that declares it.
2. Within any **derived class** (child class) that inherits from the declaring class.

**Comparison Table (1 mark each):**

| Specifier  | Same Class | Derived Class | Outside Class |
|------------|:----------:|:-------------:|:-------------:|
| `private`  |     ✅     |      ❌       |      ❌       |
| `protected`|     ✅     |      ✅       |      ❌       |
| `public`   |     ✅     |      ✅       |      ✅       |

**Key distinguishing feature:** `protected` strikes a balance — it **hides** the member from external code (like `private`) but **exposes** it to derived classes for inheritance-based extension (like `public`).

---

### Question A2. `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`
**Explain how the `protected` access specifier behaves differently in Java compared to C++.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

In **C++**, a `protected` member is accessible **only** to:
- The declaring class.
- Its derived classes (and friend classes/functions).

In **Java**, a `protected` member is accessible to:
- The declaring class **(1 mark)**.
- Any subclass in **any package**, but **only through inheritance** (i.e., on `this` or subclass-type references) **(1 mark)**.
- Any **non-derived class in the same package** (Java's unique twist — `protected` here behaves like package-private access) **(1 mark)**.

This makes Java's `protected` **slightly more permissive** than C++'s, because same-package unrelated classes can also access it. C++ has no concept of packages, so its `protected` is strictly hierarchical.

