#### Model Solution for B2(a) — Java `protected` Across Packages

**The Three Visibility Rules (3 marks):**

In Java, a `protected` member is visible in the following scenarios:
1. **Within the declaring class itself** (trivially true).
2. **Within any subclass in any package**, but **only through an inheritance context** (the subtle rule).
3. **Within any non-subclass in the same package** (package-level visibility bonus).

**The "Inherited-Only" Rule Explained (2 marks):**

A subclass in a different package can access a `protected` member of its superclass **only if the access is made via a reference of the subclass's own type** (i.e., `this` or any reference declared as the subclass or one of its further descendants). It **cannot** access the protected member through a reference of the superclass type from a client context.

**Illustrative Example (2 marks):**

**File: `bank/core/Account.java`**
```java
package bank.core;
public class Account {
    protected double balance = 10000;
    private int pin = 1234;
    public String bankName = "SBI";
}
```

**File: `bank/derivatives/SavingsAccount.java`**
```java
package bank.derivatives;
import bank.core.Account;

public class SavingsAccount extends Account {
    public void credit(double amount) {
        balance = balance + amount;        // ✅ LEGAL: subclass access via inheritance
    }

    public void viewBalance() {
        System.out.println("Balance: " + balance);
    }
}
```

**File: `bank/test/TestAccess.java`**
```java
package bank.test;
import bank.core.Account;
import bank.derivatives.SavingsAccount;

public class TestAccess {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SavingsAccount sa = new SavingsAccount();
        sa.credit(500);
        sa.viewBalance();                  // ✅ LEGAL: public method

        // System.out.println(sa.balance); // ❌ ILLEGAL: TestAccess is not a subclass of Account
        System.out.println(sa.bankName);   // ✅ LEGAL: public member
    }
}
```

