## 5.3 ⚠️ KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks in KTU Exams:**
>
> 1. **Confusing Java's `protected` with C++'s `protected`:** Java's `protected` allows same-package access for non-derived classes, while C++ does not. Students who write "In C++, `protected` means same-package access" lose **2 marks immediately**.
>
> 2. **Forgetting the "inherited-only" rule in Java:** When asked about cross-package protected access, students must specify the subclass-type-reference rule. A vague answer like "subclasses can access protected members" is worth only **1 mark** out of 3.
>
> 3. **Treating `protected` as `public` in derivation:** Students often write code where `main()` accesses protected members and expect it to compile. The exam asks for compile-error identification — be explicit about the **compile-time** error.
>
> 4. **Not mentioning the `friend` mechanism in C++:** If the question is about C++ access specifiers, mentioning `friend` functions/classes adds **bonus marks** because it shows depth of understanding.
>
> 5. **Missing the `default` (package-private) access in Java:** Java has **four** access levels, not three. Forgetting to mention the default/package-private level loses a mark in comparison questions.
>
> 6. **Writing code without access specifier comments:** In code-based questions, KTU examiners award marks for **explicitly labelling** each member as `private`, `protected`, or `public` with comments. Don't skip this.

