## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

### 🎯 Rapid Revision Checklist

- ✅ **`protected`** is the **middle-ground** access specifier — between `private` (strict) and `public` (open).
- ✅ In **C++**, `protected` members are accessible in the declaring class and all derived classes, plus friend classes/functions. **Same-package access does not apply** (C++ has no packages).
- ✅ In **Java**, `protected` members are accessible in the declaring class, all subclasses (any package, but only via inheritance), and **non-derived classes in the same package**.
- ✅ The **"inherited-only" rule** in Java: cross-package subclass access to `protected` must go through `this` or a subclass-type reference, not a base-class-type reference from outside.
- ✅ **Friend functions/classes** in C++ can access **all** members regardless of access level — this is a special exception.
- ✅ Java has **4 access levels** (private, default/package-private, protected, public); C++ has **3** (private, protected, public).
- ✅ `protected` is essential for the **Template Method design pattern**, where base classes define algorithm skeletons and derived classes fill in steps.
- ✅ `protected` **propagates down the inheritance chain** — a grandchild can access the grandparent's protected members.
- ✅ `protected` members are **NOT accessible** from `main()` or any unrelated non-derived, non-friend, non-same-package class.
- ✅ For KTU 14-mark questions, always write a **complete compilable program** with explicit access specifier labels and a `main()` function that demonstrates both legal and illegal access attempts (in comments).

### 🧠 Memory Aid: The "Three Doors" Mnemonic

Imagine three doors in a house:
- 🚪 **`private`** = **Master bedroom** — only the homeowner enters.
- 🚪 **`protected`** = **Family living room** — homeowner and children/grandchildren enter; guests do not.
- 🚪 **`public`** = **Front porch** — everyone in the world can stand there.

### 📌 Final Exam Tip

In KTU viva and written exams, when asked *"Why use `protected` over `private`?"*, the ideal answer is:

> *"When a base class intends to be **extended** through inheritance, `protected` allows derived classes to directly access the base's internal state needed for the extension, without exposing that state to the rest of the program. It is the only access level that balances encapsulation with extensibility."*
