# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Rules — The 7 Golden Rules of Abstract Classes

1. **Declaration Rule:** An abstract class is declared using the `abstract` keyword before the `class` keyword.
2. **Instantiation Rule:** Abstract classes **cannot be instantiated** using the `new` keyword directly.
3. **Abstract Method Rule:** An abstract method has **no body**; it ends with a semicolon `;`.
4. **Inheritance Rule:** A concrete (non-abstract) subclass **must implement ALL inherited abstract methods**, or it must itself be declared `abstract`.
5. **Constructor Rule:** Abstract classes **can have constructors**, which are invoked when a subclass object is created (via `super()`).
6. **Static Members Rule:** Abstract classes **can have static methods, static fields, and final methods**.
7. **Access Modifier Rule:** An abstract method **cannot be `private`** (subclasses must override it). It can be `public`, `protected`, or package-private.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why these rules exist (the "Why" behind the "How"):**
> - The non-instantiation rule ensures the compiler enforces design intent — you cannot accidentally use a half-built template.
> - The mandatory override rule enforces the **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)** of SOLID design — any subclass *is-a* type of the parent, so it must be a complete usable entity.

## 2.2 Syntax Skeleton

```java
// ABSTRACT CLASS
abstract class Shape {

    String color;                                  // Instance field allowed

    Shape(String color) {                          // Constructor allowed
        this.color = color;
    }

    // ABSTRACT METHOD (no body, ends with ;)
    abstract double area();

    // CONCRETE METHOD (full implementation)
    public void displayColor() {
        System.out.println("Color: " + color);
    }
}

// CONCRETE SUBCLASS (must implement all abstract methods)
class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;

    Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}
```

## 2.3 Abstract Class vs Concrete Class — High-Yield Comparison Table

| Property | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|----------|----------------|----------------|
| `abstract` keyword | Required | Not used |
| Can be instantiated? | **No** | **Yes** |
| Can have abstract methods? | **Yes** (0 or more) | **No** (not allowed) |
| Can have concrete methods? | **Yes** | **Yes** |
| Can have constructors? | **Yes** | **Yes** |
| Can have `static` methods? | **Yes** | **Yes** |
| Can have `final` methods? | **Yes** | **Yes** |
| Purpose | Blueprint / partial implementation | Complete implementation |

## 2.4 Abstract Class vs Interface — A Critical Distinction

Although interfaces in Java can now (Java 8+) have default and static methods, abstract classes still differ in important ways:

| Property | Abstract Class | Interface |
|----------|----------------|-----------|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Inheritance type | Single (extends) | Multiple (implements) |
| Method types | Abstract + concrete | Abstract + default + static |
| Fields | Any (instance/static) | Only `public static final` (constants) |
| Constructor | Allowed | **Not allowed** |
| Access modifiers | Any | `public` only (implicit) |
| `main()` method | Allowed | Allowed (static) |

> [!NOTE]
> **Use Abstract Class when:** subclasses share a common *state* (fields) and *implementation*, and you want to enforce a partial contract.
> **Use Interface when:** you want to define a pure contract / capability that unrelated classes can implement (e.g., `Serializable`, `Comparable`).

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

Abstract classes are foundational in many real engineering systems:

- **Java Collections Framework:** `AbstractList`, `AbstractMap`, `AbstractSet` provide partial implementations that concrete classes like `ArrayList`, `HashMap` extend.
- **GUI Frameworks:** `javax.swing.AbstractButton` is extended by `JButton`, `JToggleButton`, `JMenuItem`.
- **Template Method Pattern:** Frameworks (Spring, Struts) define algorithm skeletons in abstract base classes; user code supplies specific steps.
- **Game Development:** An abstract `Enemy` class with abstract `attack()` method, extended by `Zombie`, `Dragon`, `Robot` — each with its own attack behavior.

## 2.6 KTU High-Yield Declaration Patterns

| Pattern | Valid? | Notes |
|---------|--------|-------|
| `abstract class A { }` | ✅ | Abstract class with no abstract methods (legal but unusual) |
| `abstract class A { abstract void m(); }` | ✅ | Standard abstract method |
| `abstract class A { void m() { } }` | ✅ | All methods concrete; class still abstract |
| `class A extends B {}` where `B` has abstract `m()` | ❌ | Compilation error — `A` must implement `m()` or be `abstract` |
| `new AbstractClassName(...)` | ❌ | Compilation error — cannot instantiate |
| `abstract final class A` | ❌ | Illegal combination — `final` prevents inheritance, `abstract` requires it |
| `abstract private void m();` | ❌ | Illegal — `private` prevents overriding |
| `abstract static void m();` | ❌ | Illegal — `static` cannot be overridden |

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall:** Many students incorrectly write `abstract void m() { }` (with empty body). This is a **compilation error**. The body of an abstract method is replaced by a semicolon — **never empty braces**.

