# Section 3: Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthrough & Code Derivations

## 3.1 Worked Example 1 — Basic Abstract Class Hierarchy

**Problem:** Design an abstract class `BankAccount` with an abstract method `calculateInterest()`. Create concrete subclasses `SavingsAccount` and `CurrentAccount` that compute interest differently.

### Step 1 — Declare the abstract superclass

```java
abstract class BankAccount {
    String accountHolder;
    double balance;

    BankAccount(String accountHolder, double balance) {
        this.accountHolder = accountHolder;
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    // Abstract method — no body
    abstract double calculateInterest();

    // Concrete method — full implementation
    void displayDetails() {
        System.out.println("Holder : " + accountHolder);
        System.out.println("Balance: " + balance);
    }
}
```

### Step 2 — Derive the concrete subclass `SavingsAccount`

```java
class SavingsAccount extends BankAccount {
    double rate;

    SavingsAccount(String holder, double balance, double rate) {
        super(holder, balance);          // Calls abstract class constructor
        this.rate = rate;
    }

    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return balance * rate / 100.0;   // Simple interest formula
    }
}
```

### Step 3 — Derive the concrete subclass `CurrentAccount`

```java
class CurrentAccount extends BankAccount {
    double maintenanceCharge;

    CurrentAccount(String holder, double balance, double charge) {
        super(holder, balance);
        this.maintenanceCharge = charge;
    }

    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        // No interest; deduct maintenance charge
        return -maintenanceCharge;
    }
}
```

### Step 4 — Driver class demonstrating polymorphism

```java
public class BankDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // BankAccount ref = new BankAccount(...);   // ❌ ILLEGAL
        BankAccount acc1 = new SavingsAccount("Arjun", 50000, 4.5);
        BankAccount acc2 = new CurrentAccount("Meera", 75000, 500);

        System.out.println("Savings Interest : " + acc1.calculateInterest());
        System.out.println("Current Interest : " + acc2.calculateInterest());
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Savings Interest : 2250.0
Current Interest : -500.0
```

### Step-by-Step Numeric Trace

For `acc1` (SavingsAccount, balance=50000, rate=4.5):

$$\text{Interest} = \frac{\text{balance} \times \text{rate}}{100} = \frac{50000 \times 4.5}{100} = 2250.0$$

For `acc2` (CurrentAccount, balance=75000, charge=500):

$$\text{Interest} = -\text{maintenanceCharge} = -500.0$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Polymorphism in action:** The reference type is `BankAccount` (abstract), but the actual method invoked is determined at **runtime** by the JVM based on the object's real type (`SavingsAccount` or `CurrentAccount`). This is **dynamic method dispatch** — a classic KTU high-yield concept.

## 3.2 Worked Example 2 — Abstract Class with Zero Abstract Methods

This is a frequently tested edge case in KTU exams.

```java
abstract class Utility {
    static int count = 0;

    Utility() {
        count++;
    }

    public static void showCount() {
        System.out.println("Objects created: " + count);
    }

    // No abstract methods — yet class is still abstract!
}

class Tool extends Utility {
    // Inherits everything; no method to override
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Utility u = new Utility();   // ❌ Compile error
        new Tool();
        new Tool();
        Utility.showCount();             // ✅ Static method callable
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Objects created: 2
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why make it abstract if there are no abstract methods?**
> To **restrict instantiation** while still allowing shared state and behavior. Used in utility/helper hierarchies and as part of the **Template Method Pattern** where the skeleton is in the base class.

## 3.3 Worked Example 3 — The Template Method Pattern (KTU Favourite)

The **Template Method Pattern** is a behavioral design pattern where an abstract class defines the *skeleton* of an algorithm in a concrete method, but defers specific steps to abstract methods that subclasses override.

```java
abstract class DataParser {

    // TEMPLATE METHOD — final so subclasses cannot change the algorithm
    public final void parse() {
        readFile();
        processData();          // abstract
        writeOutput();           // abstract
        System.out.println("Parsing complete.\n");
    }

    void readFile() {                          // Concrete step
        System.out.println("Reading file...");
    }

    abstract void processData();
    abstract void writeOutput();
}

class CSVParser extends DataParser {
    @Override
    void processData() {
        System.out.println("Processing CSV rows...");
    }
    @Override
    void writeOutput() {
        System.out.println("Writing CSV report.");
    }
}

class JSONParser extends DataParser {
    @Override
    void processData() {
        System.out.println("Parsing JSON tree...");
    }
    @Override
    void writeOutput() {
        System.out.println("Writing JSON report.");
    }
}

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        DataParser p1 = new CSVParser();
        p1.parse();

        DataParser p2 = new JSONParser();
        p2.parse();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Reading file...
Processing CSV rows...
Writing CSV report.
Parsing complete.

Reading file...
Parsing JSON tree...
Writing JSON report.
Parsing complete.
```

### Step-by-Step Logic Trace

| Step | CSVParser trace | JSONParser trace |
|------|----------------|------------------|
| 1. `readFile()` | Inherited from `DataParser` | Inherited from `DataParser` |
| 2. `processData()` | Overridden → "Processing CSV rows..." | Overridden → "Parsing JSON tree..." |
| 3. `writeOutput()` | Overridden → "Writing CSV report." | Overridden → "Writing JSON report." |
| 4. `System.out.println` | Same | Same |

The algorithm structure stays the same; only the variable steps differ. This is the **essence of the Template Method Pattern** — controlled extensibility.

## 3.4 Analytical Decision Matrix — When to Use Abstract Class

| Situation | Use Abstract Class? | Reasoning |
|-----------|---------------------|-----------|
| Subclasses share common fields/state | ✅ **Yes** | Abstract classes can hold instance variables; interfaces cannot. |
| Need constructors to initialize shared state | ✅ **Yes** | Interfaces cannot have constructors. |
| Want partial implementation in the base | ✅ **Yes** | Concrete methods can provide default behavior. |
| Need to inherit from multiple sources | ❌ **No** | Java doesn't support multiple class inheritance; use interfaces. |
| Pure contract definition (no state) | ❌ **No** | Prefer interface. |
| Need to define constants used by many unrelated classes | ❌ **No** | Prefer interface with `public static final` fields. |
| Framework defines algorithm skeleton, user fills in steps | ✅ **Yes** | Classic Template Method use case. |

## 3.5 Common Compilation Errors — KTU Exam Pitfalls

| Code | Error | Reason |
|------|-------|--------|
| `abstract void m() {}` | Missing method body | Empty `{}` is treated as a body; abstract methods must end with `;` |
| `new AbstractClass()` | Cannot instantiate | Compiler error — abstract class not instantiable |
| `abstract final class A` | Illegal combination | `final` prevents extension, contradicting abstract's need for inheritance |
| Subclass missing override | "Inherited abstract method not implemented" | Subclass must implement all abstract methods or itself be abstract |
| `abstract static void m();` | Illegal modifier combination | `static` methods cannot be overridden; abstract requires overriding |
| `private abstract void m();` | Illegal modifier combination | `private` hides method; cannot be overridden |

