## Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Q1. **[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
**What is an abstract class in Java? Why can't it be instantiated?**

**Model Answer:**

An abstract class in Java is a class declared with the `abstract` keyword that may contain abstract methods (methods without a body) and concrete methods (with implementation). It serves as an incomplete blueprint for subclasses.

**Why it cannot be instantiated:**
- An abstract class represents a *partial implementation* — it may have unimplemented abstract methods.
- The Java compiler prevents calling `new AbstractClassName()` because an object of an abstract class would be "incomplete" and could not respond to all declared methods.
- Instantiation is restricted by a compile-time check enforced by the JVM specification; doing so would violate the design contract.

```java
abstract class Animal { abstract void sound(); }
// Animal a = new Animal();   // ❌ Compile error
```

---

### Q2. **[KTU University Exam — June 2024]**
**Differentiate between an abstract class and a concrete class in Java.**

**Model Answer:**

| Property | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|----------|----------------|----------------|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `class` |
| Instantiation | Not allowed | Allowed |
| Abstract methods | May contain | Cannot contain |
| Purpose | Blueprint / partial contract | Complete usable type |

A concrete class is one where **all methods have implementations**, making it a fully usable type that can be instantiated. An abstract class may have unimplemented methods, so it remains an incomplete template and is used only for inheritance.

