### **Question A (14 Marks)** — **[KTU University Exam — May 2024, Set A]**

**(a)** [7 Marks] Explain abstract classes and abstract methods in Java with suitable examples. List any **four** rules of abstract classes.

**(b)** [7 Marks] Write a Java program to create an abstract class `Employee` with abstract method `calculateSalary()`. Derive two classes `FullTimeEmployee` and `PartTimeEmployee` and demonstrate polymorphism.

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Definition:** An abstract class is declared using the `abstract` keyword and may contain abstract methods (declared without a body) and concrete methods (with body). It cannot be instantiated but can be subclassed.

**Four Key Rules:**

1. **Cannot be instantiated:** `new AbstractClass()` causes a compile-time error.
2. **Abstract method has no body:** It ends with a semicolon `;`, not braces `{}`.
3. **Mandatory override:** Concrete subclasses must implement *all* inherited abstract methods, or declare themselves abstract.
4. **Constructors allowed:** Abstract classes can have constructors called via `super()` in subclasses.

**Example:**
```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract void start();
    void stop() { System.out.println("Vehicle stopped."); }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    void start() { System.out.println("Car started with key."); }
}
```

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

```java
abstract class Employee {
    String name;
    double basePay;

    Employee(String name, double basePay) {
        this.name = name;
        this.basePay = basePay;
    }

    abstract double calculateSalary();

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Salary: " + calculateSalary());
        System.out.println("----------------------");
    }
}

class FullTimeEmployee extends Employee {
    FullTimeEmployee(String n, double b) { super(n, b); }
    @Override
    double calculateSalary() {
        return basePay + (basePay * 0.20);   // 20% benefits
    }
}

class PartTimeEmployee extends Employee {
    int hours;
    PartTimeEmployee(String n, double b, int h) { super(n, b); this.hours = h; }
    @Override
    double calculateSalary() {
        return basePay * hours;              // hourly pay
    }
}

class EmployeeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new FullTimeEmployee("Anand", 30000);
        Employee e2 = new PartTimeEmployee("Leena", 250, 40);

        e1.display();
        e2.display();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Name: Anand
Salary: 36000.0
----------------------
Name: Leena
Salary: 10000.0
----------------------
```

**Explanation of polymorphism:** The reference type `Employee` (abstract) holds objects of `FullTimeEmployee` and `PartTimeEmployee`. The call `calculateSalary()` is resolved at **runtime** using dynamic method dispatch — this is runtime polymorphism in action.

