### **Question B (14 Marks)** — **[KTU University Exam — May 2024, Set B]**

**(a)** [7 Marks] What is the Template Method design pattern? Explain how abstract classes are used to implement it with a Java program.

**(b)** [7 Marks] Discuss the differences between an **abstract class** and an **interface** in Java. State when each is preferred.

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Template Method Pattern** is a behavioral design pattern in which an abstract class defines the *skeleton of an algorithm* in a concrete method (the "template method"), while deferring specific steps to abstract methods that subclasses override.

**Key Idea:** The overall algorithm structure remains unchanged; only certain steps vary across subclasses. The template method is typically declared `final` to prevent subclasses from altering the algorithm flow.

**Java Program — Data Processing Pipeline:**

```java
abstract class DataMiner {

    // TEMPLATE METHOD - final to lock the algorithm
    public final void mine() {
        openFile();
        extractData();         // abstract step
        parseData();           // abstract step
        analyzeData();         // concrete step
        sendReport();
        closeFile();
    }

    void openFile()  { System.out.println("Opening file..."); }
    void closeFile() { System.out.println("Closing file..."); }
    void analyzeData() { System.out.println("Analyzing patterns..."); }
    void sendReport() { System.out.println("Sending report..."); }

    abstract void extractData();
    abstract void parseData();
}

class PDFDataMiner extends DataMiner {
    @Override
    void extractData() { System.out.println("Extracting text from PDF..."); }
    @Override
    void parseData()   { System.out.println("Parsing PDF tokens..."); }
}

class CSVDataMiner extends DataMiner {
    @Override
    void extractData() { System.out.println("Reading CSV rows..."); }
    @Override
    void parseData()   { System.out.println("Splitting CSV fields..."); }
}

class TemplateDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        DataMiner dm1 = new PDFDataMiner();
        dm1.mine();
        System.out.println();

        DataMiner dm2 = new CSVDataMiner();
        dm2.mine();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Opening file...
Extracting text from PDF...
Parsing PDF tokens...
Analyzing patterns...
Sending report...
Closing file...

Opening file...
Reading CSV rows...
Splitting CSV fields...
Analyzing patterns...
Sending report...
Closing file...
```

**Advantages:**
- Code reuse: shared steps written once in the abstract class.
- Controlled extension: subclasses can only override designated steps.
- Consistency: the algorithm flow is locked in the base class.

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

**Abstract Class vs Interface:**

| Property | Abstract Class | Interface |
|----------|----------------|-----------|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Inheritance | A class can extend **only one** abstract class | A class can implement **multiple** interfaces |
| Method types | Abstract + concrete (instance/static) | Abstract + default + static (Java 8+) |
| Fields | Any (instance, static, final) | Only `public static final` constants |
| Constructor | Allowed | Not allowed |
| Access modifiers | Any | Implicitly `public` |
| State | Can hold instance state (fields) | Stateless (only constants) |
| When to use | Shared code + partial contract among related classes | Pure contract / capability across unrelated classes |

**When to prefer Abstract Class:**
- When subclasses share **common state** (fields) and **common behavior** (concrete methods).
- When you need **constructors** to initialize shared fields.
- Example: `AbstractList<E>` in Java Collections.

**When to prefer Interface:**
- When defining a **capability** (e.g., `Serializable`, `Cloneable`, `Comparable`) that unrelated classes may possess.
- When **multiple inheritance** of type is needed.
- Example: A `Bird` class and an `Airplane` class can both implement `Flyable` interface.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall (Repeated Mistake):**
> 1. Many students write `abstract void m() { }` — this is a **compilation error**. An abstract method body must be replaced with `;`.
> 2. Students forget that an abstract class **can have a constructor**, and that it is called via `super()` in the subclass.
> 3. Some students declare an abstract class and then try `AbstractClass obj = new AbstractClass();` — this loses 2 marks immediately.
> 4. In polymorphism questions, students often write the **reference type** and **object type** in reverse — losing marks for the conceptual understanding.
> 5. Confusing `abstract` with `interface` — remember interfaces cannot have constructors or instance fields.

---

## Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Abstract class** = `abstract class A { }` — cannot be instantiated, may have abstract + concrete methods.
- **Abstract method** = `abstract returnType methodName();` — no body, ends with `;`.
- A concrete subclass **must implement ALL** inherited abstract methods, or itself be declared abstract.
- Abstract classes **can have constructors**, called via `super()` from the subclass.
- Abstract classes **can have static, final, and instance fields/methods**.
- You **cannot** combine `abstract` with `final` or `private` or `static`.
- **Template Method Pattern** uses an abstract class to define algorithm skeleton; subclasses fill in specific steps.
- Abstract classes enable **runtime polymorphism** via dynamic method dispatch.
- **Abstract class vs Interface** = state-sharing partial contract vs pure capability contract.
- Polymorphism question pattern: superclass reference → subclass object → overridden method invoked at runtime.
- KTU high-yield keywords to memorize: `abstract`, `extends`, `super()`, `@Override`, dynamic dispatch, Template Method.
- Common errors to avoid: instantiating abstract class, missing override, empty body `{}` on abstract method, illegal modifier combinations.

