# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Walkthrough — Anatomy of a `throw` Statement

Below is a fully derived Java program demonstrating every nuance of `throw` behavior. We will trace it line-by-line.

### Example 1 — Basic `throw` with RuntimeException

```java
class VoterValidator {
    static void validateAge(int age) {
        if (age < 18) {
            // Step 1: Instantiate exception object explicitly
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age " + age + " is not eligible to vote.");
        }
        System.out.println("Voter is eligible.");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            validateAge(15);  // Will trigger throw
            System.out.println("This line will NOT execute.");
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        System.out.println("Program continues normally.");
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Trace

**Step 1:** `main()` invokes `validateAge(15)`.
**Step 2:** Inside `validateAge`, condition `15 < 18` evaluates to `true`.
**Step 3:** A new `IllegalArgumentException` object is created with the message `"Age 15 is not eligible to vote."`. This object is allocated on the heap.
**Step 4:** The `throw` statement initiates stack unwinding. The `System.out.println("Voter is eligible.")` line becomes **unreachable** for this execution.
**Step 5:** JVM searches for a matching `catch (IllegalArgumentException e)` block in `main()`. Found!
**Step 6:** The catch block executes, printing `"Exception caught: Age 15 is not eligible to vote."`
**Step 7:** Program continues with `System.out.println("Program continues normally.")`.

**Output:**
```
Exception caught: Age 15 is not eligible to vote.
Program continues normally.
```

### Example 2 — Multiple `throw` Statements in a Method

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

class DivisionEngine {
    static double divide(int a, int b) {
        if (b == 0) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("Division by zero not allowed.");
        }
        if (a < 0 || b < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Negative numbers not permitted.");
        }
        return (double) a / b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            System.out.println("Result 1: " + divide(10, 0));
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Math Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        try {
            System.out.println("Result 2: " + divide(-5, 3));
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Input Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        try {
            System.out.println("Result 3: " + divide(20, 4));
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Generic Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Math Error: Division by zero not allowed.
Input Error: Negative numbers not permitted.
Result 3: 5.0
```

### Example 3 — Rethrowing a Caught Exception (Advanced)

```java
class RethrowDemo {
    static void methodA() throws Exception {
        try {
            throw new NullPointerException("Original error in methodA");
        } catch (NullPointerException e) {
            System.out.println("Logged in methodA: " + e.getMessage());
            throw e;  // Rethrow the same exception object
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            methodA();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Final handler: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Logged in methodA: Original error in methodA
Final handler: Original error in methodA
```

### Analytical Matrix — When to Use Which Exception Type with `throw`

| Business Condition | Recommended Exception Class | Inheritance Path |
|-------------------|----------------------------|------------------|
| Invalid input arguments | `IllegalArgumentException` | `RuntimeException` → `Exception` → `Throwable` |
| Object state invalid for operation | `IllegalStateException` | `RuntimeException` → `Exception` |
| Null value where object required | `NullPointerException` | `RuntimeException` → `Exception` |
| Index out of bounds | `IndexOutOfBoundsException` | `RuntimeException` → `Exception` |
| Custom business rule violation | User-defined class extending `Exception` (checked) | Custom hierarchy |

### Mathematical Representation of Stack Unwinding

Let us formalize the stack unwinding process. Define:

$$
\text{Stack}_i = \text{Stack frame at depth } i \text{ in the call stack}
$$

Let $\text{ExceptionType}(e)$ denote the runtime class of exception object $e$. The unwinding algorithm proceeds as:

$$
\text{Handler}(e) = \begin{cases} \text{Stack}_j.\text{catch}(e) & \text{if } \exists\, j \leq i : \text{ExceptionType}(e) \subseteq \text{Stack}_j.\text{catchClass} \\ \text{defaultHandler}() & \text{if } \forall\, j : \text{no match found} \end{cases}
$$

In words: the JVM searches from the innermost stack frame outward (decreasing $j$), and the **first matching** catch block handles the exception. If no match exists up to and including `main()`, the JVM default handler prints the stack trace and terminates.

