## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ `throw` is used to **explicitly** raise an exception object from within a method body.
- ✅ The operand of `throw` must be a **Throwable instance**, never a class name.
- ✅ Only **one** exception object can be thrown per `throw` statement.
- ✅ Statements following `throw` in the same block are **unreachable**.
- ✅ **Checked exceptions** thrown via `throw` require either a `try-catch` or a `throws` declaration in the method signature.
- ✅ **Unchecked exceptions** (`RuntimeException` subclasses) do not require `throws` declaration.
- ✅ `throw` initiates **stack unwinding**, transferring control to the nearest matching `catch` block.
- ✅ If no matching catch is found up to `main()`, the JVM default handler terminates the program with a stack trace.
- ✅ `throw` can **rethrow** a caught exception inside a `catch` block for logging or exception chaining.
- ✅ `throw` ≠ `throws` — `throw` is an action (verb), `throws` is a declaration (signature modifier).
- ✅ A method can have **multiple throw statements**, but only one executes per method invocation.
- ✅ Custom exceptions should extend `Exception` (checked) or `RuntimeException` (unchecked) depending on whether the calling code should be forced to handle them.

