# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Working with Files in Java

### Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus)
Java provides a rich set of classes in the **`java.io`** and **`java.nio.file`** packages to handle file operations. A file is an abstract resource managed by the operating system, and Java encapsulates it through streams — abstract channels of data flow. File handling in Java follows the **Decorator Design Pattern**, where a stream object is wrapped inside another stream to add functionality (e.g., buffering, serialization).

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Definition (Board Term):** A *Stream* is a logical connection between a Java program and a physical device (file, keyboard, network socket). It represents a sequence of data flowing in (Input) or flowing out (Output).

### Two Major Stream Hierarchies
| Stream Type | Unit | Base Classes | Used For |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Byte Streams** | 1 byte (8 bits) | `InputStream`, `OutputStream` | Binary files (images, audio, executables) |
| **Character Streams** | 2 bytes (16-bit Unicode) | `Reader`, `Writer` | Text files (.txt, .java, .csv) |

### Intuitive Analogy
Imagine a **water pipeline** connecting a reservoir (file on disk) to your house (Java program).
- **InputStream/Reader** = pipes carrying water *into* your house.
- **OutputStream/Writer** = pipes taking water *out* of your house.
- **Buffer** = a *water tank* attached to the pipe. You don't open the tap for every sip; water fills the tank first, and you draw from the tank — making it efficient.
- **File** object = the *address* of the reservoir; you can't drink from an address, you need the pipeline to actually fetch water.

