## 1.2 String Constructors

### Formal Definition
A **`String`** in Java is an immutable object (defined in `java.lang` package) that represents a sequence of `char` values backed internally by a `char[]` (prior to Java 9) or a `byte[]` (compact strings from Java 9 onwards). The `String` class provides **overloaded constructors** to instantiate `String` objects from various sources: another `String`, character arrays, byte arrays, `StringBuffer`, and `StringBuilder`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why multiple constructors?** Because data can arrive from any source — a network packet (byte array), a tokenized CSV (character array), a mutable buffer (`StringBuffer`), or simply a literal. Each constructor is a conversion mechanism from one data form to a `String`.

### Intuitive Analogy
Think of `String` constructors as **translators at a UN conference**.
- A French delegate (`char[]`) needs a translator to speak English (`String`).
- A written document in German (`byte[]`) needs a different translator.
- A live speaker updating their notes (`StringBuffer`) needs yet another translator.
Each constructor is a *specific translator* tuned to the input format. Once translated to English (`String`), the speech is **frozen and immutable** — exactly like a `String` object.

---

