# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 Architecture of Java I/O (Decorator Pattern)

The entire Java I/O library is built on the **Decorator Pattern**. A base stream provides core functionality, and a decorator stream wraps it to add features.

### Operation Flow (Step-by-Step)
1. **Source/Sink** — physical file, keyboard, network socket.
2. **Node Stream** — directly connects to source/sink (`FileInputStream`, `FileReader`).
3. **Processing Stream (Decorator)** — wraps the node stream to enhance it (`BufferedInputStream`, `DataInputStream`).
4. **Application Program** — reads from the outermost stream.

### Hierarchy Diagram (Textual)

```
                Object
                  |
          +-------+--------+
          |                |
     InputStream      OutputStream
          |                |
   FileInputStream   FileOutputStream
          |                |
   BufferedInputStream  BufferedOutputStream
          |                |
   DataInputStream    DataOutputStream
   ObjectInputStream  ObjectOutputStream
          |
          +--- (similar mirror tree for Reader/Writer)
```

### Stream Selection Cheat Sheet
| Use Case | Recommended Classes |
|---|---|
| Read text file line-by-line | `BufferedReader` wrapping `FileReader` |
| Write text to file | `BufferedWriter` wrapping `FileWriter` |
| Read binary data (int, double, etc.) | `DataInputStream` wrapping `FileInputStream` |
| Write binary data | `DataOutputStream` wrapping `FileOutputStream` |
| Copy a file | `FileInputStream` → `FileOutputStream` (with a buffer) |
| Serialize an object | `ObjectOutputStream` wrapping `FileOutputStream` |
| Append to a file | `FileWriter(path, true)` or `FileOutputStream(path, true)` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Always close streams** by calling `close()` — preferably inside a `finally` block, or use **try-with-resources** (Java 7+) which auto-closes resources.

### try-with-resources Syntax (Modern Best Practice)
```java
try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("input.txt"));
     BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output.txt"))) {
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        bw.write(line);
        bw.newLine();
    }
} // br and bw are auto-closed here, even if exception occurs
```

