## 2.2 KTU High-Yield Constructor Reference Table for `String`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Board Exam Pattern:** KTU frequently asks *"Explain any 5 constructors of String class with examples"* (7 marks) or *"Discuss String class constructors in detail"* (14 marks). Memorize the table below thoroughly.

| # | Constructor Signature | Description | Example |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `String()` | Creates empty String (length 0) | `String s = new String();` |
| 2 | `String(String original)` | Creates copy of the argument | `String s = new String("Hello");` |
| 3 | `String(char[] value)` | Creates from entire char array | `new String(new char[]{'J','a','v','a'})` → `"Java"` |
| 4 | `String(char[] value, int offset, int count)` | Subarray → String | `new String(new char[]{'J','a','v','a'}, 1, 2)` → `"av"` |
| 5 | `String(byte[] bytes)` | Default charset decoding | `new String(new byte[]{65, 66})` → `"AB"` |
| 6 | `String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length)` | Subarray with default charset | `new String(new byte[]{65,66,67,68}, 1, 2)` → `"BC"` |
| 7 | `String(byte[] bytes, Charset charset)` | Explicit charset | `new String(bytes, StandardCharsets.UTF_8)` |
| 8 | `String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length, Charset charset)` | Subarray + explicit charset | (combination) |
| 9 | `String(byte[] bytes, String charsetName)` | Throws `UnsupportedEncodingException` | `new String(bytes, "UTF-8")` |
| 10 | `String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length, String charsetName)` | Subarray + charset name | (combination) |
| 11 | `String(int[] codePoints, int offset, int count)` | Unicode code points → String | `new String(new int[]{65, 66}, 0, 2)` → `"AB"` |
| 12 | `String(StringBuffer buffer)` | Snapshot of mutable buffer | `new String(new StringBuffer("Hi"))` → `"Hi"` |
| 13 | `String(StringBuilder builder)` | Snapshot of mutable builder | `new String(new StringBuilder("Hi"))` → `"Hi"` |
| 14 | `String(byte[] ascii, int hibyte, int offset, int count)` | **DEPRECATED** since Java 1.1 | Avoid in code |
| 15 | `String(char[] value, boolean share)` | **Package-private** (JVM internal) | Not for application use |

### Mathematical View of Subarray Constructors

For any array `A` of size $n$, extracting a subarray produces:

$$
\text{length}_{\text{new}} = \text{count} \leq n - \text{offset}
$$

**Boundary Condition for Valid Construction:**

$$
0 \le \text{offset} < \text{length}(A) \quad \text{AND} \quad 0 \le \text{count} \le \text{length}(A) - \text{offset}
$$

If violated, the constructor throws `StringIndexOutOfBoundsException`.

### Why a Special Constructor for `StringBuffer`/`StringBuilder`?

The objects `StringBuffer` and `StringBuilder` are **mutable**, while `String` is **immutable**. The `String(StringBuffer)` constructor performs a defensive copy — at the moment of construction, it freezes the mutable buffer's content into an immutable `String`. Any subsequent modification to the buffer does **not** affect the created `String`.

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Real-World Use:** In network programming, data often arrives as a `byte[]` (raw bytes from a socket). The `String(byte[], Charset)` constructor is the safest way to convert it to a `String`, because you explicitly specify the encoding (e.g., UTF-8) — preventing platform-dependent bugs.

