# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Step-by-Step: A Complete File Handling Program

**Problem:** Write a Java program to read a text file `input.txt` and write its uppercase version to `output.txt`, using character streams with buffering.

```java
import java.io.*;

public class FileCopyUpper {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // ---- STEP 1: Open streams (node streams first, then decorators) ----
        try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("input.txt"));
             BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output.txt"))) {

            // ---- STEP 2: Read line by line until EOF (null returned) ----
            String line;
            int lineCount = 0;
            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
                lineCount++;

                // ---- STEP 3: Transform ----
                String upper = line.toUpperCase();

                // ---- STEP 4: Write transformed line ----
                bw.write(upper);
                bw.newLine();        // Platform-independent newline
            }

            System.out.println("Copied " + lineCount + " lines successfully.");

        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.err.println("File not found: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.err.println("I/O Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        // ---- STEP 5: Streams auto-closed by try-with-resources ----
    }
}
```

### Detailed Walkthrough — Line by Line

| Line | Purpose | KTU Examiner Note |
|---|---|---|
| `new FileReader("input.txt")` | Node stream → connects to file | Throws `FileNotFoundException` |
| `new BufferedReader(...)` | Decorator → adds buffer + `readLine()` | Buffer default: 8192 chars |
| `br.readLine()` | Reads up to `\n`, `\r`, or `\r\n`; returns `null` at EOF | Returns `String` (no `\n` included) |
| `line.toUpperCase()` | Locale-independent uppercase conversion | Uses `Locale.getDefault()` (caveat) |
| `bw.write(upper)` | Writes the String | Does **not** add a newline |
| `bw.newLine()` | Inserts platform-specific line separator | Use this, not `"\n"` |
| `try (...)` | Try-with-resources (Java 7+) | Auto-closes all resources |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Read Question Carefully:** "Read characters from a file and display on console" → use `System.out` after reading. "Copy a file" → use two streams (input + output). "Read binary data" → use `DataInputStream`.

