## 3.3 Step-by-Step: Demonstrating Each String Constructor

```java
public class StringConstructorsDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws UnsupportedEncodingException {

        // Constructor 1: String() — empty string
        String s1 = new String();
        System.out.println("s1 = '" + s1 + "' length=" + s1.length());

        // Constructor 2: String(String original) — copy
        String s2 = new String("Hello");
        System.out.println("s2 = " + s2);

        // Constructor 3: String(char[] value)
        char[] ch1 = {'J', 'a', 'v', 'a'};
        String s3 = new String(ch1);
        System.out.println("s3 = " + s3);

        // Constructor 4: String(char[] value, int offset, int count)
        String s4 = new String(ch1, 1, 2);   // from index 1, take 2 chars
        System.out.println("s4 = " + s4);    // "av"

        // Constructor 5: String(byte[] bytes) — default platform charset
        byte[] b1 = {65, 66, 67, 68};        // 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D'
        String s5 = new String(b1);
        System.out.println("s5 = " + s5);

        // Constructor 6: String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length)
        String s6 = new String(b1, 1, 2);    // 'B', 'C'
        System.out.println("s6 = " + s6);

        // Constructor 7: String(byte[] bytes, Charset charset)
        String s7 = new String(b1, java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
        System.out.println("s7 = " + s7);

        // Constructor 8: String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length, Charset charset)
        String s8 = new String(b1, 1, 2, java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
        System.out.println("s8 = " + s8);

        // Constructor 9: String(byte[] bytes, String charsetName) — throws checked exception
        String s9 = new String(b1, "US-ASCII");
        System.out.println("s9 = " + s9);

        // Constructor 10: String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length, String charsetName)
        String s10 = new String(b1, 1, 2, "US-ASCII");
        System.out.println("s10 = " + s10);

        // Constructor 11: String(int[] codePoints, int offset, int count)
        int[] codePoints = {72, 73, 32, 8364};  // 'H','I',' ','€'
        String s11 = new String(codePoints, 0, codePoints.length);
        System.out.println("s11 = " + s11);

        // Constructor 12: String(StringBuffer buffer) — defensive copy
        StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer("Mutable");
        String s12 = new String(sb);
        sb.append(" Modified");                  // Mutates the buffer
        System.out.println("s12 = " + s12);      // "Mutable" — unaffected!

        // Constructor 13: String(StringBuilder builder)
        StringBuilder sbd = new StringBuilder("Builder");
        String s13 = new String(sbd);
        sbd.append(" Modified");
        System.out.println("s13 = " + s13);      // "Builder" — unaffected!
    }
}
```

### Trace Table — Subarray Constructors

Let $A = \{'J', 'a', 'v', 'a'\}$ (length = 4).

| Call | offset | count | Characters used | Result |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `new String(A)` | 0 | 4 (implicit) | All | `"Java"` |
| `new String(A, 0, 4)` | 0 | 4 | `'J','a','v','a'` | `"Java"` |
| `new String(A, 1, 2)` | 1 | 2 | `'a','v'` | `"av"` |
| `new String(A, 2, 1)` | 2 | 1 | `'v'` | `"v"` |
| `new String(A, 4, 0)` | 4 | 0 | (none) | `""` (empty) |
| `new String(A, 1, 5)` | 1 | 5 | — | **`StringIndexOutOfBoundsException`** |

### Why the Defensive Copy Matters (StringBuffer Example)

Let $B = \text{"Mutable"}$, then `String s = new String(B)`.

After the line `B.append(" Modified")`:

- $B$ becomes `"Mutable Modified"`.
- $s$ remains `"Mutable"` — **immutable** snapshot.

Mathematically:

$$
\text{String}(B)_{\text{time}=t_0} \rightarrow \text{copy of } B_{t_0}
$$

$$
\forall t > t_0 : s = B_{t_0} \ne B_t
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **This is the key reason `String` is immutable** — when you need to "freeze" a mutable structure for use as a key in a `HashMap` or to ensure thread-safety, the `String(StringBuffer)` constructor gives you a guaranteed snapshot.

