## 3.4 Step-by-Step: Writing Binary Data Using `DataOutputStream`

```java
import java.io.*;

public class BinaryWriteRead {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // ---- WRITE SIDE ----
        try (DataOutputStream dos = new DataOutputStream(
                new BufferedOutputStream(
                    new FileOutputStream("data.bin")))) {

            dos.writeInt(2024);          // 4 bytes
            dos.writeDouble(3.14159);    // 8 bytes
            dos.writeUTF("KTU");         // 2-byte length + UTF-8 bytes
            dos.writeBoolean(true);      // 1 byte

            System.out.println("Binary data written.");

        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // ---- READ SIDE ----
        try (DataInputStream dis = new DataInputStream(
                new BufferedInputStream(
                    new FileInputStream("data.bin")))) {

            int year   = dis.readInt();
            double pi  = dis.readDouble();
            String tag = dis.readUTF();
            boolean b  = dis.readBoolean();

            System.out.println("Year : " + year);
            System.out.println("Pi   : " + pi);
            System.out.println("Tag  : " + tag);
            System.out.println("Flag : " + b);

        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Binary data written.
Year : 2024
Pi   : 3.14159
Tag  : KTU
Flag : true
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`writeUTF`/`readUTF`** use a **modified UTF-8** format (2-byte length prefix). They are **not** the same as plain UTF-8. To use standard UTF-8, manually convert with `getBytes("UTF-8")` and `new String(bytes, "UTF-8")`.

