## KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks in This Topic:**
>
> 1. **Confusing `File` class with actual file I/O.** The `File` class *cannot read or write content* — it only manages paths. Writing `File f = new File("test.txt"); f.write("hi");` is a **fatal error** worth −2 marks.
>
> 2. **Forgetting to pass `true` for append mode.** In `new FileOutputStream(path, true)`, omitting `true` will **overwrite** the destination file. Examiners explicitly check this.
>
> 3. **Using `read()` and comparing with `null` instead of `-1`.** Both `FileInputStream.read()` and `FileReader.read()` return an `int` (0–255 or -1). Writing `while (fr.read() != null)` is a **compile error** that loses 1–2 marks.
>
> 4. **String constructor signature errors.** The exact signature `String(char[] value, int offset, int count)` must be remembered. Students often write `String(char[], int, int)` without names — partial credit only.
>
> 5. **Not handling `FileNotFoundException` separately.** It is a *checked* subclass of `IOException` and must be caught or declared. Missing it = compilation failure.
>
> 6. **Mixing `String` and `StringBuilder` constructors.** `String(StringBuilder)` exists; `String(String)` is a different constructor. Examiners test if you know **both** exist.
>
> 7. **Forgetting `StringIndexOutOfBoundsException` boundary check.** Subarray constructors with `offset`/`count` can throw this — the marks go to those who *mention* the exception explicitly.

