# 🧵 Creating Multiple Threads in Java

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus)

In the context of **Object Oriented Programming** under the **KTU 2024 Scheme**, a **Thread** is defined as the smallest unit of execution within a Java process. The **Java Virtual Machine (JVM)** allows an application to have **two or more parts of program code running concurrently**, where each part is termed a *thread*. The act of **creating multiple threads** refers to the procedural mechanism by which a developer instantiates more than one independent path of execution within a single Java program to perform multiple tasks simultaneously, thereby achieving **concurrency** and improved CPU utilization.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (PEEIT741 - Module 4):**
> The official KTU 2024 syllabus groups *Thread fundamentals, thread creation (via `Thread` class and `Runnable` interface), thread lifecycle, and thread priorities* under Module 4. **Creating multiple threads** is the foundational skill tested frequently in both Continuous Evaluation (CE) and End Semester Examinations (ESE).

## 1.2 Why Do We Need Multiple Threads?

Consider a single-threaded program: only one task executes at a time, and subsequent tasks must wait. This is inefficient when:
- A task is **I/O bound** (waiting for user input, file read, network call).
- A task is **CPU-intensive** and we want to keep the UI responsive.

**Multiple threads** allow a program to perform several operations seemingly at the same time (on single-core CPUs via time-slicing, or truly parallel on multi-core CPUs).

## 1.3 Conceptual Analogy — The Restaurant Kitchen 🍳

Imagine a **restaurant kitchen**:
- A **single-threaded chef** must complete one dish fully before starting the next. If dish #1 needs 5 minutes of baking (waiting time), the chef stands idle.
- A **multi-threaded kitchen** employs multiple chefs (threads): Chef A bakes bread (and waits), Chef B chops vegetables, Chef C plates food. All three progress **concurrently**, dramatically increasing throughput.

In Java terms:
- The **kitchen** = JVM / process
- Each **chef** = an independent thread
- The **recipe** = the `run()` method
- The **head chef assigning work** = the main thread invoking `start()`

> [!NOTE]
> **Core Distinction:** Concurrency ≠ Parallelism. **Concurrency** = multiple tasks making progress in overlapping time periods (single core can do this). **Parallelism** = multiple tasks executing *exactly* at the same instant (requires multiple cores). Java threads support both, depending on hardware.

## 1.4 Two Official Ways to Create a Thread in Java

The **Java API (`java.lang` package)** officially defines **two standard mechanisms** for creating multiple threads. The KTU examiner almost always tests both — be prepared to compare them in any 14-mark question.

| # | Mechanism | Base Class/Interface | Best Use Case |
|---|-----------|----------------------|----------------|
| **1** | Extending the `java.lang.Thread` class | Class Inheritance | When the thread class itself must be enhanced with new behavior |
| **2** | Implementing the `java.lang.Runnable` interface | Interface Implementation | When the class must inherit from another class (Java does not support multiple class inheritance) |

We will analyze both approaches exhaustively in **Section 2** and **Section 3**.

