# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 The `java.lang.Thread` Class — Core Architecture

The `Thread` class (in package `java.lang`) encapsulates all thread functionality. Its critical static and instance members are summarized below.

### 2.1.1 Key Constructors of `Thread` Class

| Constructor | Purpose |
|-------------|---------|
| `Thread()` | Creates a thread with a default name `Thread-N`. |
| `Thread(String name)` | Creates a thread with the supplied human-readable name. |
| `Thread(Runnable target)` | Creates a thread that will execute the `run()` of the supplied `Runnable` object. |
| `Thread(Runnable target, String name)` | Combines the previous two — assigns both a `Runnable` task and a name. |
| `Thread(ThreadGroup group, Runnable target, String name)` | Used for advanced grouping of threads for collective management. |

### 2.1.2 Key Methods of `Thread` Class

| Method | Signature Type | Purpose |
|--------|----------------|---------|
| `start()` | Instance | **Registers the thread with the thread scheduler and invokes `run()` in a new call stack.** Calling `start()` more than once throws `IllegalThreadStateException`. |
| `run()` | Instance | The entry point of the new thread. Override it to define the task. **Calling `run()` directly does NOT start a new thread — it executes in the current thread.** |
| `sleep(long ms)` | Static | Suspends the **currently executing** thread for `ms` milliseconds. Does not release the lock. |
| `join()` | Instance | The calling thread waits until the target thread finishes execution. |
| `yield()` | Static | A *hint* to the scheduler that the current thread is willing to pause so others of equal priority can run. |
| `getName()` / `setName(String)` | Instance | Read/write the thread's name. |
| `getPriority()` / `setPriority(int)` | Instance | Priority range is **1 (MIN_PRIORITY)** to **10 (MAX_PRIORITY)**; default is **5 (NORM_PRIORITY)**. |
| `isAlive()` | Instance | Returns `true` if the thread has been started and not yet died. |
| `currentThread()` | Static | Returns a reference to the currently executing thread object. |
| `interrupt()` | Instance | Interrupts a sleeping/waiting thread by setting its interrupt flag. |

> [!NOTE]
> **The Single Most Important Method — `start()` vs `run()`:**
> This is a **favourite KTU question**. Always remember:
> - `t.start()` → **New thread is created**; the thread scheduler eventually calls `t.run()`.
> - `t.run()` → **No new thread is created**; it executes like a normal method call in the calling thread.

## 2.2 The `java.lang.Runnable` Interface

`Runnable` is a **functional interface** (single abstract method: `void run()`). Any class that *implements* `Runnable` can be passed to a `Thread` constructor, decoupling the *task* (what to do) from the *thread* (worker doing it).

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Runnable {
    void run();
}
```

## 2.3 Thread Lifecycle States (KTU High-Yield Diagram Topic)

A thread exists in one of the following **six states** as defined in the Java specification:

1. **New** — Object created, `start()` not yet called.
2. **Runnable** — `start()` called; thread is ready to run, waiting for CPU.
3. **Blocked** — Waiting to acquire a monitor lock (e.g., entering a `synchronized` block).
4. **Waiting** — `Object.wait()`, `Thread.join()`, `LockSupport.park()` invoked — waits indefinitely until another thread notifies.
5. **Timed_Waiting** — `sleep(ms)`, `wait(ms)`, `join(ms)`, `LockSupport.parkNanos()` — waits for a specified time.
6. **Terminated** — `run()` method has finished execution normally or via exception.

### 2.3.1 KTU Lifecycle Transition Table

| From State | Triggering Method | To State |
|------------|-------------------|----------|
| New | `start()` | Runnable |
| Runnable | Scheduler picks thread | Running (subset of Runnable in modern JVM) |
| Running | `yield()` | Runnable |
| Running | `sleep()` / `wait(t)` / `join(t)` | Timed_Waiting |
| Running | `wait()` / `join()` / `park()` | Waiting |
| Running | Acquires monitor lock after contention | Runnable |
| Any (except New) | `run()` completes or uncaught exception | Terminated |

## 2.4 Approach 1 — Extending the `Thread` Class (Detailed)

**Step-by-step logic:**
1. Define a subclass of `java.lang.Thread`.
2. Override the `public void run()` method — this holds the task code.
3. In `main()`, instantiate the subclass object.
4. Call `start()` on the object to spawn a *new* call stack executing `run()`.
5. To create **multiple threads**, instantiate the subclass multiple times and call `start()` on each.

### 2.4.1 Structural Skeleton

```java
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        // task code goes here
    }
}
```

## 2.5 Approach 2 — Implementing the `Runnable` Interface (Detailed)

**Step-by-step logic:**
1. Create a class that `implements Runnable`.
2. Implement the `public void run()` method.
3. In `main()`, instantiate: `MyRunnable r = new MyRunnable();`
4. Pass the `Runnable` object to a `Thread` constructor: `Thread t = new Thread(r, "Worker-1");`
5. Call `t.start()`.
6. **Critical KTU fact:** The same `Runnable` instance can be passed to *multiple* `Thread` objects, and **all those threads will share the same target object** — useful for shared data scenarios.

### 2.5.1 Structural Skeleton

```java
class MyTask implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        // task code goes here
    }
}
```

## 2.6 Comparison: `Thread` vs `Runnable` (High-Yield Table)

| Criterion | Extending `Thread` | Implementing `Runnable` |
|-----------|--------------------|--------------------------|
| Inheritance flexibility | Cannot extend another class (Java's single inheritance) | Can extend another class |
| Object reusability | Each thread needs its own subclass object | Same `Runnable` can be passed to many `Thread` objects |
| Object-oriented purity | Couples task and worker (violates *"favor composition over inheritance"*) | Decouples task and worker — cleaner OOP design |
| Memory footprint | Heavier (subclass inherits all `Thread` fields) | Lighter (just the task object) |
| Recommended by Java docs | Acceptable | **Recommended** |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner's Note:** In 14-mark comparison questions, always conclude with the line: *"Implementing `Runnable` is preferred in real-world OOP design because it supports multiple inheritance of type and enables multiple threads to share the same resource object."*

## 2.7 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **GUI Applications (Swing/JavaFX):** Event Dispatch Thread + worker threads prevent UI freeze.
- **Web Servers (Tomcat, Netty):** Each incoming request handled on its own thread.
- **Database Connection Pools:** Background threads clean idle connections.
- **Game Development:** One thread for rendering, one for physics, one for input.
- **Banking Systems:** Concurrent transaction validation.

