# 3. Step-by-Step Walkthrough — Creating Multiple Threads

> [!NOTE]
> This section provides **fully annotated, executable code** with exhaustive step-by-step analysis. Every output line is justified.

## 3.1 Method 1 — Extending `Thread` Class (Multiple Threads)

### 3.1.1 Full Code Listing

```java
class WorkerThread extends Thread {
    public WorkerThread(String name) {
        super(name);   // initialize parent Thread with this name
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println(getName() + " - Count: " + i);
            try {
                Thread.sleep(500);   // pause for 500 ms
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                System.out.println(getName() + " interrupted.");
            }
        }
        System.out.println(getName() + " finished execution.");
    }
}

public class MultiThreadDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        WorkerThread t1 = new WorkerThread("Thread-A");
        WorkerThread t2 = new WorkerThread("Thread-B");
        WorkerThread t3 = new WorkerThread("Thread-C");

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
        t3.start();
    }
}
```

### 3.1.2 Line-by-Line Conceptual Walkthrough

1. `class WorkerThread extends Thread` — inherits all thread machinery (priority, name, scheduler hooks).
2. `super(name)` — invokes `Thread(String name)` constructor to assign a human-readable name.
3. `@Override public void run()` — **this is the new thread's entry point**, NOT a regular method.
4. `Thread.sleep(500)` — the **current** thread (the one in whose stack we are) pauses for 500 ms. After 500 ms, it becomes runnable again.
5. `t1.start()` — registers `t1` with the **Thread Scheduler** (part of the JVM, ultimately mapped to the OS). The scheduler picks a thread to run; the JVM calls `t1.run()` on a fresh call stack.
6. `t2.start()` and `t3.start()` — three independent call stacks now exist, all competing for CPU time.

### 3.1.3 Sample Output (Order Varies)

```
Thread-A - Count: 1
Thread-B - Count: 1
Thread-C - Count: 1
Thread-A - Count: 2
Thread-B - Count: 2
...
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Exam Tip:** In the answer sheet, you MUST explicitly state *"The exact order of execution is non-deterministic and depends on the underlying thread scheduler and OS."* Examiners specifically look for this phrase — it carries 1–2 marks.

## 3.2 Method 2 — Implementing `Runnable` Interface (Multiple Threads)

### 3.2.1 Full Code Listing

```java
class PrintTask implements Runnable {
    private final char targetChar;

    public PrintTask(char targetChar) {
        this.targetChar = targetChar;
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName()
                               + " prints " + targetChar + " (iteration " + i + ")");
            try {
                Thread.sleep(400);
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                System.out.println("Interrupted!");
            }
        }
    }
}

public class RunnableDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PrintTask taskA = new PrintTask('*');
        PrintTask taskB = new PrintTask('#');
        PrintTask taskC = new PrintTask('@');

        Thread t1 = new Thread(taskA, "Star-Worker");
        Thread t2 = new Thread(taskB, "Hash-Worker");
        Thread t3 = new Thread(taskC, "At-Worker");

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
        t3.start();
    }
}
```

### 3.2.2 Step-by-Step Walkthrough

1. `PrintTask` is a **POJO** (plain object) holding *only* the task — no thread machinery.
2. `Thread.currentThread().getName()` — used inside `run()` because we are no longer inside a `Thread` subclass, so we cannot call `getName()` directly.
3. Three different `PrintTask` instances (`taskA`, `taskB`, `taskC`) are wrapped into three different `Thread` instances.
4. Calling `start()` on each `Thread` creates three concurrent call stacks executing their respective `run()` methods.

## 3.3 Method 3 — Sharing a Single `Runnable` Among Multiple Threads (Advanced KTU Concept)

This is the **classic KTU 14-mark question** testing deeper understanding.

### 3.3.1 Full Code Listing

```java
class SharedTicketCounter implements Runnable {
    private int availableTickets = 5;

    @Override
    public void run() {
        // multiple threads share the SAME availableTickets field
        while (availableTickets > 0) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName()
                               + " sold ticket #" + availableTickets);
            availableTickets--;
            try {
                Thread.sleep(100);
            } catch (InterruptedException e) { }
        }
    }
}

public class SharedRunnableDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SharedTicketCounter counter = new SharedTicketCounter(); // SINGLE object

        Thread agent1 = new Thread(counter, "Agent-1");
        Thread agent2 = new Thread(counter, "Agent-2");
        Thread agent3 = new Thread(counter, "Agent-3");

        agent1.start();
        agent2.start();
        agent3.start();
    }
}
```

### 3.3.2 Analytical Walkthrough

1. A **single** `SharedTicketCounter` object is created.
2. **Three `Thread` objects** are constructed, all receiving the **same** `counter` reference.
3. When all three threads call `start()`, the JVM creates three independent stacks, but **all three stacks' `run()` methods manipulate the same `availableTickets` instance variable** of the shared object.
4. This demonstrates **shared state in multithreading** — a precursor to synchronization issues (covered in Module 4's later sections).

## 3.4 Anonymous Class / Lambda Variant (Modern Java)

Since `Runnable` is a **functional interface**, we can use a lambda expression (introduced in Java 8).

```java
public class LambdaThreadDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Runnable task = () -> {
            for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
                System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " -> " + i);
            }
        };

        new Thread(task, "Lambda-T1").start();
        new Thread(task, "Lambda-T2").start();
    }
}
```

### 3.4.1 Walkthrough

1. The lambda `() -> { ... }` is a concise implementation of the `Runnable.run()` method.
2. Both `Lambda-T1` and `Lambda-T2` share the same `task` object and will print interleaved output.
3. This is the modern, idiomatic Java way to create threads.

## 3.5 Mathematical Model of Concurrency Speedup (Optional but High-Yield)

For CPU-bound tasks, **Amdahl's Law** estimates the theoretical speedup:

$$
S(N) = \frac{1}{(1 - P) + \frac{P}{N}}
$$

Where:
- $S(N)$ = speedup factor using $N$ threads
- $P$ = proportion of code that is parallelizable (a fraction between 0 and 1)
- $N$ = number of threads

### 3.5.1 Sample Calculation

Suppose $P = 0.8$ (80% parallelizable) and $N = 4$ threads:

$$
S(4) = \frac{1}{(1 - 0.8) + \frac{0.8}{4}}
$$

$$
S(4) = \frac{1}{0.2 + 0.2} = \frac{1}{0.4} = 2.5
$$

So with 4 threads, the program runs **2.5× faster**, not 4× — because 20% of the code is sequential.

> [!NOTE]
> This formula rarely appears in OOP papers but may surface in a tricky *application-level* question. Keep it in your peripheral memory.

