### **Question A — 14 Marks** *(Full Module Choice Option 1)*

#### **Part (a) [7 marks]**
**Explain the two ways of creating threads in Java with suitable examples. Compare them.**

#### **Model Answer:**

**Introduction (1 mark):**
A thread in Java is a lightweight subprocess — the smallest unit of processing. Java provides two standard mechanisms to create threads: (i) extending the `java.lang.Thread` class, and (ii) implementing the `java.lang.Runnable` interface.

**Method 1: Extending `Thread` class (2.5 marks):**

```java
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public MyThread(String name) { super(name); }
    @Override
    public void run() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
            System.out.println(getName() + " : " + i);
        }
    }
}
public class Test1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t1 = new MyThread("A");
        MyThread t2 = new MyThread("B");
        t1.start(); t2.start();
    }
}
