## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning ⚠️

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Pitfalls Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting to override `run()` (–2 marks):** Writing `start()` on a class that *extends Thread* but does not override `run()` will simply call the empty `Thread.run()` from the parent class. Output will be empty.
> 2. **Calling `run()` instead of `start()` (–2 marks):** This is the *#1 most common error*. The program will run sequentially with no concurrency. Always invoke `start()`.
> 3. **Calling `start()` twice on the same object (–2 marks):** Throws `IllegalThreadStateException` at runtime. Examiners love to test this.
> 4. **Forgetting to handle `InterruptedException` in `sleep()` / `join()` (–1 to –3 marks):** Causes a compile-time error. Always wrap in `try-catch`.
> 5. **Writing `start()` in a non-`Runnable` implementing class (–2 marks):** Only classes extending `Thread` or whose object is wrapped in a `Thread` can use `start()`. Plain `Runnable` objects cannot be started directly.
> 6. **Confusing priorities with guarantees (–1 mark):** Priority is a *hint*, not a hard rule. Writing *"setting priority guarantees the thread runs first"* is factually wrong.
> 7. **Missing the `currentThread()` inside `Runnable.run()` (–1 mark):** Inside an interface implementation, `getName()` is not available — you must call `Thread.currentThread().getName()`.

